92	\begin{document}
93	\maketitle
94	
95	\begin{abstract}
96	We study Reed--Solomon codes evaluated on smooth multiplicative domains: subgroups $H\le\F_q^\times$ of power-of-two order $n$, at fixed rate $\rho=k/n$, the domains of deployed proximity-testing protocols.  This merged corrected edition consolidates two complementary developments into a single document with an explicit proof-status ledger: the list/entropy route based on locator fibers, quotient cores, characteristic-zero rigidity, and Galois-amplified reduction collisions (Part~I); and the slack mutual-correlated-agreement (MCA) theory based on the exact bad-slope calculus, failure ladders, density positive results, direction arithmetic, quotient floors, and residue-line normal forms (Part~II).
97	
98	On the list side, the negative conclusions are unconditional: the coefficient-pigeonhole mechanism gives exponential lists below the ambient entropy scale, and quotient cores force superpolynomial lists at the deployed dyadic rates --- more generally along any quotient-divisible scale $M\mid k$ --- whenever $\sigma=o(n/\log n)$, refuting the one-scale ambient-$q$ entropy-gap prediction even over prime fields.  Any polynomial-list theorem must therefore use a corrected reserve of the form $\tau\gtrsim\max\{\taustar(\rho,q_D),\,c_{\rho,B}/\log n\}$, with subfield variants governed by the field of definition.  The positive structural results are: arbitrary list size reduces to locator fibers; over characteristic zero, equal prefix fibers among subsets of $2$-power roots of unity are exactly quotient-periodic; and in prime fields $p\equiv1\pmod n$ a Galois-amplified norm argument shows that for $p>\exp(Cn\log n/\sigma)$ every monomial-prefix finite-field collision is already a characteristic-zero quotient collision, so monomial-prefix list sizes are polynomial at the corrected reserve for split primes in the quasi-polynomial range $p>\exp(O((\log n)^2))$.
99	
100	On the MCA side, the no-slack form of the principle is false, and the corrected slack theory at radius $1-\rho-t/N$ separates proved theorems from conditional analytic inputs and open inverse problems.  The unconditional spine is the exact slack characterization of the canonical line $x^{k+T}+zx^k$, the quotient locator and coset collapse, the cyclotomic and Fermat rigidity lemmas, the two-moment square-root construction, and the dyadic descent theorem.  The free-pool results are stated as conditional consequences of a precise subgroup exponential-sum input.  On the positive side the safe-slack bookkeeping uses the effective parameter $\ceff=\sigma\log_2 n/n$; the quotient-exact floor shows the closed-form quotient count $A(N',\ell')=2^{\beta(\rho)N'(1-o(1))}$ survives at every prime above the quotient norm threshold $p>(2\ell')^{N'/2}$, giving a genuine MCA lower bound from the quotient profile at large primes and a concrete cap for several deployed-rate challenge parameters.  The earlier all-bases, all non-dyadic-direction theorem remains removed (its rigidity step is false for arbitrary bases) and replaced by a Newton-obstruction criterion and the valid zero-base theorem.
101	
102	A transfer part extends the mechanisms beyond the smooth multiplicative prime-field setting.  A subfield-confinement theorem decouples the two grand challenges over deployed extension fields: $B$-valued lines have all MCA-bad slopes in $B$, deflating every prime-field witness to density $|B|/|\F|<2^{-154}$ at the deployed sextic parameters, while quotient-core lists persist verbatim.  The quotient-core and slack-one mechanisms transfer to Dickson--Chebyshev quotient chains, hence to circle-group $x$-coordinate Reed--Solomon constituents at Mersenne-$31$ parameters; the $\{2,3\}$-smooth relation module and set decomposition supply the mixed-radix rigidity input; and a torsion-coset template theorem, conditional on an imported effective torsion-coset bound (Laurent, Aliev--Smyth), replaces the retracted arbitrary-base claim at the level of characteristic-zero template structure.  Finally, conditional on an imported list-to-agreement conversion of Crites--Stewart, composing quotient-core lists with the conversion caps the achievable MCA threshold at challenge dimensions: for challenge codes with $n\le q/2$ over any field of size at most $2^{256}$, the error is at least $2^{-42}$ already at gap $2^{-11}$.  The sharpened, final form of this cap --- gap $2^{-9}$ ($2^{-10}$ at rate $1/16$), error $2^{-86}$ with no condition relating $n$ and $q$, and extension fields included --- is proved in the companion cap paper \cite{UniversalCap}, which this edition cross-references throughout.
103	
104	The document closes with an integrated frontier: the final threshold statements are isolated as finite-field local-limit conjectures for locator fibers and residue lines, calibrated on both sides by the same two-scale, floor-corrected reserve.  We do not claim the full polynomial-field list theorem or the all-line MCA positive theorem as proved.
105	\end{abstract}
106	
107	\tableofcontents
108	
109	\section{Introduction}\label{sec:intro}
110	
111	Proximity testing protocols \cite{FRI,WHIR} fold pairs of oracles $f,g$ into random combinations $u_z=f+zg$ and rest their soundness on a mutual correlated agreement principle: if $u_z$ agrees with a Reed--Solomon codeword on a large support, then $f$ and $g$ should themselves agree with codewords on that support, except for a controlled set of slopes.  Capacity is $1-\rho$ at rate $\rho$; the Johnson radius is $1-\sqrt\rho$, below which proximity gaps and correlated agreement are known \cite{BCIKS20,BCHKS25}; the difficult regime lies between them, especially for the smooth multiplicative domains used by FFT-based protocols.
112	
113	The no-slack, up-to-capacity formulation is false on smooth domains \cite{NoSlack}.  Thus the right object is MCA with an explicit slack reserve.  At a quotient scale $N\mid n$ and slack $t$, the relevant radius is
114	\[
115	        1-\rho-\frac{t}{N},
116	\]
117	and the central question becomes: how many slopes are bad, and which mechanisms produce them?
118	
119	This merged edition consolidates the list/entropy route and the slack-MCA theory under a single corrected ledger: it keeps the parts that are proved from the algebraic setup and downgrades the parts that require additional fixed-prime equidistribution input.  Part~I develops the list side (locator fibers, the two lower-bound scales, characteristic-zero rigidity, and the Galois-amplified collision sieve); Part~II develops the corrected slack-MCA theory; Part~III develops transfers of the failure mechanisms beyond smooth multiplicative prime-field domains (extension fields, additive and Chebyshev/circle $x$-coordinate domains), a conditional universal field-size cap, and the torsion-coset repair of the arbitrary-base theory; Part~IV states the integrated frontier.  On the MCA side, the contributions are as follows.
120	
121	\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]
122	\item \emph{Exact slack calculus.}  The bad-slope set of the canonical slack line $x^{k+T}+zx^k$ is identified exactly as a multi-symmetric image of the evaluation set (\cref{thm:exactslack}).  The quotient locator (\cref{lem:tlocator}) and the coset-collapse proposition (\cref{prop:collapse}) explain why subgroup-symmetric slack witnesses reduce to a one-condition ladder.  Cyclotomic and digit rigidity (\cref{thm:rigidcyclo,thm:rigidfermat}) show that the remaining asymmetric witnesses are genuinely modular rather than characteristic-zero phenomena.
123	
124	\item \emph{Failure mechanisms.}  The Dias da Silva--Hamidoune theorem gives certified slack-one failure at the square-root barrier (\cref{cor:certified}), while the two-moment construction gives full coverage of $(e_1,e_2)$ under explicit square-root hypotheses (\cref{thm:twomoment,cor:twomomentmca}).  The dyadic descent theorem is retained with all divisibility assumptions made explicit (\cref{thm:descent}).  The free-pool ladder is stated conditionally on a precise subgroup exponential-sum estimate (\cref{thm:ladder}); where the cited estimates supply that estimate, the stated ranges follow, but the theorem is not used as a black-box proof of stronger fixed-prime equidistribution.
125	
126	\item \emph{Characteristic-zero rigidity and direction arithmetic.}  The inverse quotient theorem (\cref{thm:rigidity}) proves that vanishing at dyadic frequencies forces quotient invariance.  Consequently, zero-base non-dyadic directions have no characteristic-zero nonzero slopes (\cref{thm:directions}), while dyadic directions reduce to lower-level direction-one problems.  The earlier all-bases non-dyadic theorem is replaced by the Newton-obstruction criterion of \cref{thm:allbasesdir}; arbitrary bases require extra equations before the rigidity theorem can be applied.
127	
128	\item \emph{Positive density, quotient floors, and stable results.}  At deepest-level slack $\sigma$, the correct normalization is
129	\[
130	        \ceff=\frac{\sigma\log_2 n}{n}.
131	\]
132	With this bookkeeping, the canonical line has a no-threshold descent floor of order $\rho(1-\rho)(\log_2n/\ceff)^2$ at every prime and a density ceiling for at least half the admissible primes in explicit windows (\cref{thm:diag}).  The quotient-exact floor of \cref{prop:qfloor} upgrades the floor to $n^{\beta(\rho)/\ceff(1-o(1))}$ at every prime above the quotient norm threshold.  Every monomial base in the canonical direction obeys the same quotient-class cap, with a sharpened collision term (\cref{thm:allbases}).  In the stable range $p>(2s)^{n/2}$, the canonical-line and zero-base direction predictions are exact at every prime --- exactness is claimed only for these proved strata, not for arbitrary bases --- and the closed-form canonical count remains valid (\cref{thm:stable,thm:exactcount}).
133	
134	\item \emph{Boundary and conjecture.}  The exact normal form (\cref{thm:normalform}) identifies the residue-line packing number that equals MCA error after maximizing over line data.  The denominator-closure statement is kept as a coordinate normal form, not a quantitative bound (\cref{thm:closure}).  The quotient-profile lower bound (\cref{thm:qnecessity}) calibrates the necessary quotient reserve for polynomial MCA bounds at large primes, while the final conjecture remains a per-fiber packing conjecture with a separate conditional failure half (\cref{conj:B}).
135	\end{enumerate}
136	
137	
138	The merged theorem package, with proof status, is as follows.
139	
140	\begin{theorem}[Integrated theorem package, with status]\label{thm:integrated-package}
141	For smooth multiplicative domains $H$ of order $n=2^m$ at fixed rate $\rho$:
142	\begin{enumerate}[label=\textup{(\alph*)},leftmargin=2.4em]
143	\item \textup{(Proved.)}  Below the entropy scale $\taustar(\rho,q)$, explicit monomial-prefix received words have exponentially many nearby codewords (\cref{thm:pigeonhole,cor:entropy-lower}).
144	\item \textup{(Proved.)}  Independently of $q$, quotient cores produce at least $\binom{n/M-1}{k/M}$ codewords at agreement $k+\sigma$ whenever $M\mid k$, $k/M\le n/M-1$, and $\sigma<M$; consequently, at the deployed dyadic rates (and along any scale with $M\mid k$), polynomial-in-$n$ list decoding requires $\sigma=\Omega(n/\log n)$, and the one-scale ambient-$q$ entropy-gap prediction is false even over prime fields (\cref{thm:qcore,cor:one-scale-false}).
145	\item \textup{(Proved.)}  Over characteristic zero, equal prefix moments among subsets of $\mu_n$ are exactly quotient-periodic; characteristic-zero prefix fibers are polynomial once $\sigma\ge Cn/\log n$ (\cref{thm:upstairs,cor:upstairs-poly}).
146	\item \textup{(Proved.)}  If $p\equiv1\pmod n$ and $p>\exp(C_1n\log(2n)/\sigma)$, every finite-field monomial-prefix collision is quotient-periodic; monomial-prefix received words have polynomial lists at $\sigma\ge C_0n/\log_2n$ for split primes in the quasi-polynomial range $p>\exp(O((\log n)^2))$ (\cref{thm:no-collision,cor:quasipoly-upper}).
147	\item \textup{(Proved or conditional, as marked.)}  For MCA, the canonical-line bad-slope set at slack $T$ is exactly the multi-symmetric image $\mathcal B_T$ (\cref{thm:exactslack}), and subgroup-symmetric witnesses collapse onto the one-condition ladder (\cref{prop:collapse}).  Unconditional failure mechanisms are the certified slack-one rung (\cref{cor:certified}), two-moment fullness at the root barrier (\cref{thm:twomoment,cor:twomomentmca}), and dyadic descent (\cref{thm:descent}); the polynomial-range free-pool ladder is conditional on a precise subgroup exponential-sum input (\cref{thm:ladder}).  The quotient-exact floor survives at every prime above the quotient norm threshold (\cref{prop:qfloor}), the quotient profile is necessary for polynomial MCA slope bounds at large primes (\cref{thm:qnecessity}), and the deployed-rate challenge cap holds below the per-rate prime-field reach (\cref{prop:prize}).  All-line positive MCA is equivalent, up to the tangent floor, to residue-line packing (\cref{thm:normalform}).
148	\item \textup{(Proved, with imported black boxes as marked.)}  Transfers and caps: MCA-bad slopes of $B$-valued lines over an extension $\F\supseteq B$ are confined to $B$, deflating the prime-field witness theory to density at most $|B|/|\F|$ while list obstructions persist (\cref{thm:subfield,cor:deflate,cor:decouple}); the canonical locator stratum on $\F_2$-affine domains is confined to a single additive coset (\cref{prop:additive}); quotient cores and the slack-one stratum transfer to Dickson--Chebyshev and circle-group $x$-coordinate domains, with error one at Mersenne-$31$ parameters for those Reed--Solomon constituents (\cref{thm:chebqcore,prop:chebslack,cor:circle}); the $\{2,3\}$-smooth relation module gives the mixed-radix rigidity input, and arbitrary-base slabs reduce to at most $C(\sigma,s)$ torsion-coset template families under the stated effective torsion-coset import (\cref{thm:23rigidity,thm:templates,cor:reszero}); and, conditional on the imported list-to-agreement conversion of \cite{CS25}, smooth-domain challenge codes at the deployed rates with $2^{11}\mid n$, $n\le q/2$, $k\le2^{40}$, and $q\le2^{256}$ have $\emca>2^{-42}$ at gap $2^{-11}$ (\cref{thm:cap,cor:captiers}); the sharpened form --- gap $2^{-9}$, error $2^{-86}$, no field-size condition --- is \cite{UniversalCap}.
149	\item \textup{(Conjectural.)}  The full polynomial-field positive list theorem and the floor-corrected all-line MCA theorem are isolated as finite-field local-limit statements with quotient exceptions explicitly separated (\cref{conj:prefix-local,conj:arbitrary-local,conj:listprofile,conj:B,conj:final-locator,conj:final-mca}).
150	\end{enumerate}
151	\end{theorem}
152	
153	\paragraph{Setting and notation.}
154	$p$ is prime ($q$ a general prime power where stated); $D$ or $H\le\F_q^\times$ is a multiplicative subgroup of order $n$, \emph{smooth} meaning $n$ is a power of two; $C=\RS[\F_q,D,k]=\{(P(x))_{x\in D}:\deg P<k\}$ with $k=\rho n$, $\rho\in(0,1)$ fixed.  For a finite set $A$ in a field, $L_A(X)=\prod_{a\in A}(X-a)=X^{|A|}+\sum_{j\ge1}(-1)^je_j(A)X^{|A|-j}$ and $p_j(A)=\sum_{a\in A}a^j$; for $h\ge0$, $h^{\wedge}A$ is the set of sums of $h$ distinct elements of $A$.  $\HH$ is binary entropy.  Divisibility hypotheses ($\rho N\in\Z$, $t\mid N$, $t\mid\rho N$, $\sigma\mid k$, and the like) are stated where they are used.
155	
156	\part{List entropy, quotient cores, and Route 1}
157	
158	\section{List decoding as a locator-fiber problem}\label{sec:fiber}
159	
160	Every received word $y:H\to\F_q$ has a unique interpolant $U\in\F_q[X]$ of degree $<n$ on $H$.  Write $\List(y,\delta)$ for the list of codewords within relative radius $\delta$ of $y$, and $\Lst(C,\delta)=\max_y|\List(y,\delta)|$ for the worst-case list size.  A codeword $P$ agrees with $y$ on a set $S\subseteq H$ if and only if
161	\[
162	        U(X)\equiv P(X)\pmod{L_S(X)}.
163	\]
164	Since $\deg P<k$, this gives the following exact reduction.
165	
166	\begin{definition}[Locator fibers]\label{def:locator-fiber}
167	For $k<s\le n$ and $\deg U<n$, define
168	\[
169	        \Fib_U(s)=\{S\subseteq H:\ |S|=s,\ \deg(U\bmod L_S)<k\}.
170	\]
171	For monomial-prefix data $c=(c_1,\ldots,c_\sigma)\in\F_q^\sigma$, $s=k+\sigma$, define
172	\[
173	        \Phi_\sigma(S)=(e_1(S),\ldots,e_\sigma(S)),
174	        \qquad S\in\binom Hs .
175	\]
176	\end{definition}
177	
178	\begin{proposition}[Arbitrary-word fiber upper bound]\label{prop:arb-fiber}
179	For every received word $y$ with interpolant $U$,
180	\[
181	        |\List(y,1-s/n)|\le |\Fib_U(s)|.
182	\]
183	Consequently
184	\[
185	        \Lst(C,1-s/n)\le \max_{\deg U<n}|\Fib_U(s)|.
186	\]
187	\end{proposition}
188	
189	\begin{proof}
190	Each codeword $P$ agreeing with $y$ on at least $s$ coordinates has an $s$-subset $S$ of its agreement set.  Then $U\equiv P\pmod{L_S}$, so $S\in\Fib_U(s)$.  For a fixed $S$, the residue $U\bmod L_S$ is unique, hence the corresponding $P$ is unique.  Choosing one such $S$ for each listed codeword injects the list into $\Fib_U(s)$.
191	\end{proof}
192	
193	\begin{proposition}[Monomial-prefix words are exact prefix fibers]\label{prop:monomial-fiber}
194	Let $s=k+\sigma$ and
195	\[
196	        U_c(X)=X^s+\sum_{j=1}^{\sigma}(-1)^jc_jX^{s-j}.
197	\]
198	Then the map
199	\[
200	        S\longmapsto U_c-L_S
201	\]
202	is a bijection from $\Phi_\sigma^{-1}(c)$ to the list of degree-$<k$ codewords agreeing with $U_c$ on at least $s$ points.  Thus
203	\[
204	        |\List(U_c,1-s/n)|=|\Phi_\sigma^{-1}(c)|.
205	\]
206	\end{proposition}
207	
208	\begin{proof}
209	If $\Phi_\sigma(S)=c$, then the top $\sigma$ coefficients of $U_c$ and $L_S$ agree, so $P_S=U_c-L_S$ has degree $<s-\sigma=k$.  Also $P_S(x)=U_c(x)$ for $x\in S$.  Conversely, if $P$ has degree $<k$ and agrees with $U_c$ on an $s$-set $S$, then $U_c-P$ is monic of degree $s$ and vanishes exactly on $S$, hence $U_c-P=L_S$, forcing $\Phi_\sigma(S)=c$.  Injectivity follows because $L_S$ determines $S$.
210	\end{proof}
211	
212	Thus the positive half of list decoding can be stated without coding language:
213	\[
214	        \max_{\deg U<n}|\Fib_U(k+\sigma)|\quad\text{should be polynomial above the corrected reserve.}
215	\]
216	
217	\section{Two lower-bound scales}\label{sec:lower}
218	
219	The reference scale for the first mechanism is the classical entropy gap.
220	
221	\begin{definition}[Entropy gap]\label{def:taustar}
222	For $0<\rho<1$ and $q\ge2$, $\taustar(\rho,q)$ is the unique $\tau\in(0,1-\rho)$ with $\tau\log_2q=\HH(\rho+\tau)$; as $q\to\infty$ with $\rho$ fixed, $\taustar(\rho,q)=(\HH(\rho)+o(1))/\log_2q$.
223	\end{definition}
224	
225	\subsection{The entropy pigeonhole scale}\label{subsec:pigeon}
226	
227	\begin{theorem}[Coefficient pigeonhole lower bound]\label{thm:pigeonhole}
228	Let $1\le\sigma\le n-k$ and $s=k+\sigma$.  There exists a monomial-prefix word $U_c$ such that
229	\[
230	        |\List(U_c,1-s/n)|\ge \frac{1}{q^\sigma}\binom ns.
231	\]
232	\end{theorem}
233	
234	\begin{proof}
235	The map $\Phi_\sigma:\binom Hs\to\F_q^\sigma$ has $\binom ns$ inputs and at most $q^\sigma$ outputs.  Some fiber has size at least $q^{-\sigma}\binom ns$.  Apply \Cref{prop:monomial-fiber}.
236	\end{proof}
237	
238	\begin{corollary}[Generated-field pigeonhole]\label{cor:genfield-pigeonhole}
239	If $H\subseteq B$ for a subfield $B\le\F_q$ of size $q_D$, then $\Phi_\sigma$ has image in $B^\sigma$ --- its coordinates $e_j(S)$ are elementary symmetric functions of subsets of $H\subseteq B$ --- so the pigeonhole improves to
240	\[
241	        |\List(U_c,1-s/n)|\ \ge\ \frac{1}{q_D^{\,\sigma}}\binom ns
242	\]
243	for some monomial-prefix word $U_c$ with coefficients in $B$.  This is the form consumed by the necessary half of \cref{conj:listprofile}, which states the entropy floor at the generated field; in locator-fiber form, the same one-line strengthening is the subfield pigeonhole of \cite[Lem.\ ``locator fibers are lists'']{UniversalCap}.
244	\end{corollary}
245	
246	\begin{proof}
247	Identical to \cref{thm:pigeonhole} with $\F_q^\sigma$ replaced by $B^\sigma$: $e_j(S)\in B$ for every $S\subseteq H$, so $\Phi_\sigma$ has at most $q_D^{\,\sigma}$ outputs.
248	\end{proof}
249	
250	\begin{corollary}[Failure below the entropy gap]\label{cor:entropy-lower}
251	If $q=2^{o(n)}$, $\sigma=\tau n$, and
252	\[
253	        \sigma\log_2q\le (1-\eps)\log_2\binom n{k+\sigma},
254	\]
255	then some received word has list size at least
256	\[
257	        2^{\eps n\HH(\rho+\tau)-o(n)}.
258	\]
259	In particular, this gives $2^{\Omega(n)}$-size lists for every fixed multiplicative gap below the entropy scale, $\tau\le(1-\eps_0)\taustar(\rho,q)$ with $\eps_0>0$ fixed; for $\eps_0\to0$ the displayed pigeonhole bound still applies but may be subexponential.
260	\end{corollary}
261	
262	\begin{proof}
263	By \cref{thm:pigeonhole}, some monomial-prefix word has list size at least
264	\[
265	        q^{-\sigma}\binom n{k+\sigma}
266	        =2^{\log_2\binom n{k+\sigma}-\sigma\log_2q}
267	        \ge2^{\eps\log_2\binom n{k+\sigma}},
268	\]
269	and $\log_2\binom n{k+\sigma}=n\HH(\rho+\tau)-o(n)$.  For the last sentence, set $h(\tau)=\HH(\rho+\tau)$ and $g(\tau)=\tau\log_2q/h(\tau)$ on $(0,1-\rho)$.  Concavity of $h$ gives $h(\tau)-\tau h'(\tau)\ge h(0)=\HH(\rho)>0$, so $g$ is strictly increasing, and $g(\taustar)=1$ by the definition of $\taustar$.  If $\tau\le(1-\eps_0)\taustar$ with fixed $\eps_0>0$, then concavity again gives $h((1-\eps_0)\taustar)\ge(1-\eps_0)h(\taustar)+\eps_0\HH(\rho)$, whence
270	\[
271	        g(\tau)\le g\big((1-\eps_0)\taustar\big)
272	        \le\frac{(1-\eps_0)h(\taustar)}{(1-\eps_0)h(\taustar)+\eps_0\HH(\rho)}
273	        \le 1-c,
274	        \qquad
275	        c:=\frac{\eps_0\HH(\rho)}{1+\eps_0\HH(\rho)}>0,
276	\]
277	uniformly in $q$, using $h\le1$.  Thus $\sigma\log_2q\le(1-c)\,n\HH(\rho+\tau)$, and the displayed bound is at least $2^{c\,n\HH(\rho+\tau)-o(n)}=2^{\Omega_{\rho,\eps_0}(n)}$: on $[\rho,\rho+\taustar]$ the entropy is at least $\min\{\HH(\rho),\HH(\rho+\taustar)\}$, and $\HH(\rho+\taustar)=\taustar\log_2q$ cannot be small for fixed $\rho$, since otherwise $\rho+\taustar\to1$ would force $\taustar\log_2q\ge\taustar\to1-\rho>0$, a contradiction.
278	\end{proof}
279	
280	\subsection{The quotient-core scale}\label{subsec:qcore}
281	
282	The entropy scale is not the only obstruction.  Smooth subgroups have quotient structure that random domains do not have.
283	
284	\begin{theorem}[Quotient-core list obstruction]\label{thm:qcore}
285	Let $H\le\F_q^\times$ have order $n$.  Let $K\le H$ have order $M$, put $N=n/M$, and assume $M\mid k$ and $k/M\le N-1$.  If $1\le\sigma<M$, then there is a received word $Y:H\to\F_q$ with at least
286	\[
287	        \binom{N-1}{k/M}
288	\]
289	codewords agreeing with $Y$ on $k+\sigma$ coordinates.  Equivalently,
290	\[
291	        \Lst\big(\RS[\F_q,H,k],1-\rho-\sigma/n\big)\ge \binom{n/M-1}{k/M}.
292	\]
293	\end{theorem}
294	
295	\begin{proof}
296	Choose one $K$-coset $C_0\subset H$ and choose $T\subset C_0$ with $|T|=\sigma$.  Let
297	\[
298	        L_T(X)=\prod_{t\in T}(X-t),\qquad Y(X)=X^kL_T(X).
299	\]
300	For every subset $A$ of the quotient $H/K\setminus\{C_0\}$ of size $k/M$, let $U_A\subset H$ be the union of the $K$-cosets in $A$.  Since each $K$-coset is a fiber of $x\mapsto x^M$, its locator has the form $X^M-\alpha$.  Hence
301	\[
302	        L_A(X)=\prod_{x\in U_A}(X-x)=\prod_{\alpha\in A'}(X^M-\alpha)
303	        =X^k+c_1X^{k-M}+c_2X^{k-2M}+\cdots .
304	\]
305	Thus $X^k-L_A(X)$ has degree at most $k-M$.  Define
306	\[
307	        P_A(X)=Y(X)-L_T(X)L_A(X)=L_T(X)(X^k-L_A(X)).
308	\]
309	Since $\deg L_T=\sigma<M$, we have $\deg P_A<k$, so $P_A$ is a codeword.  On $T\cup U_A$, either $L_T$ or $L_A$ vanishes, so $P_A=Y$.  The agreement set has size $\sigma+k$.  Distinct $A$ give distinct locators and distinct codewords.
310	\end{proof}
311	
312	\begin{corollary}[The one-scale ambient-$q$ conjecture is false]\label{cor:one-scale-false}
313	Fix a deployed rate $\rho=2^{-a}$ and $\eps>0$.  There are infinitely many smooth prime-field domains $H\le\F_p^\times$ with $|H|=n$ and
314	\[
315	        p=2^{\Theta(\sqrt n)}
316	\]
317	such that at radius
318	\[
319	        1-\rho-(1+\eps+o(1))\taustar(\rho,p)
320	\]
321	the list size is at least
322	\[
323	        p^{1/(2(1+\eps))-o(1)}=2^{\Theta(\sqrt n)},
324	\]
325	which is superpolynomial in $n$.
326	\end{corollary}
327	
328	\begin{proof}
329	Take $n=2^m$.  By the prime number theorem in arithmetic progressions in a Siegel--Walfisz range \cite{Dav00}, there are primes $p\equiv1\pmod n$ with $\log_2p=\Theta(\sqrt n)$ for all large $n$ along a suitable sequence.  Let $H\le\F_p^\times$ have order $n$.  Since $p$ is prime, there is no proper subfield obstruction.
330	
331	Let $\sigma=\lceil(1+\eps)\taustar(\rho,p)n\rceil$.  Because $\taustar(\rho,p)=(\HH(\rho)+o(1))/\log_2p$, we have $\sigma=\Theta(\sqrt n)$.  Let $M$ be the least power of two larger than $\sigma$.  For large $n$, $M\mid k=\rho n$ and $M\le2\sigma$.  \Cref{thm:qcore} gives
332	\[
333	        L\ge \binom{n/M-1}{k/M}.
334	\]
335	By Stirling,
336	\[
337	        \log_2 L\ge \frac{n}{M}\HH(\rho)-o(n/M)
338	        \ge \frac{\HH(\rho)+o(1)}{2(1+\eps)\taustar(\rho,p)}
339	        =\left(\frac1{2(1+\eps)}-o(1)\right)\log_2p .
340	\]
341	\end{proof}
342	
343	\begin{remark}[Corrected reserve]\label{rem:corrected-reserve}
344	For a list bound $n^B$, the quotient-core family at $\sigma=Cn/\log_2n$ has size about $n^{\HH(\rho)/C}$ on the grid.  Thus a theorem with list bound $n^B$ must have $C\gtrsim \HH(\rho)/B$ at the second scale.  For unspecified polynomial list size, the necessary scale is $\sigma=\Omega(n/\log n)$; for fixed exponent $B$, the constant matters.
345	\end{remark}
346	
347	\begin{definition}[Quotient-core profile]\label{def:qprofile}
348	For a smooth domain $H$ of order $n$ and $k=\rho n$,
349	\[
350	        \mathcal Q_H(\eta)\ :=\ \max_{\substack{M\mid\gcd(n,k),\ \lceil\eta n\rceil<M\\ k/M\le n/M-1}}\ \log_2\binom{n/M-1}{k/M}
351	\]
352	($-\infty$ over the empty set): the logarithmic size of the largest quotient-core list still active at gap $\eta$.  Correspondingly, every quotient contribution of the form $2^{(\beta(\rho)/\HH(\rho))\mathcal Q_H(\eta)(1+o(1))}$ below is read as zero when the defining maximum is empty.
353	\end{definition}
354	
355	\begin{conjecture}[Quotient-profile corrected list entropy gap]\label{conj:listprofile}
356	Let $C_n=\RS[\F_{q_n},H_n,\rho n]$ with $\mathrm{poly}(n)\le q_n\le2^{o(n)}$ and $q_{D,n}$ the generated-field size, and fix a list target $n^B$.  Necessary for $\Lst(C_n,1-\rho-\eta_n)\le n^B$ is
357	\[
358	        \eta_n\ \ge\ (1-o(1))\,\taustar(\rho,q_{D,n}),
359	        \qquad
360	        \mathcal Q_{H_n}(\eta_n)\ \le\ B\log_2n+O(\log\log n)
361	\]
362	(\cref{cor:genfield-pigeonhole,thm:qcore}); the conjectural positive half is that, after fixed slack in both inequalities, the conditions are sufficient.  On dyadic domains at the deployed rates the scale form is $\eta_n\gtrsim\max\{\taustar(\rho,q_{D,n}),\,\Theta_{\rho,B}(1/\log n)\}$.
363	\end{conjecture}
364	
365	\section{Characteristic-zero inverse quotient theorem}\label{sec:upstairs}
366	
367	We now prove that, over characteristic zero, the quotient-core phenomenon is the entire prefix-fiber structure for $2$-power roots.  This is the toric Manin--Mumford/torsion-coset part of the program (compare the torsion-coset theorem \cite{Laurent84} and the theory of vanishing sums of roots of unity \cite{CJ76,LL00}), but for $2$-primary roots it has an elementary proof.
368	
369	Let $n=2^m$, let $\zeta=e^{2\pi i/n}$, and identify $\mu_n=\langle\zeta\rangle$ with the complex $n$-th roots of unity.  For $h:\mu_n\to\Z$, define
370	\[
371	        \widehat h(j)=\sum_{x\in\mu_n}h(x)x^j\in\Z[\zeta].
372	\]
373	
374	\begin{lemma}[Antipodal identity]\label{lem:antipodal}
375	Let $n'=2^r$ with $r\ge1$, and let $g:\mu_{n'}\to\Z$.  If
376	\[
377	        \sum_{y\in\mu_{n'}}g(y)y=0,
378	\]
379	then $g(y)=g(-y)$ for every $y\in\mu_{n'}$.
380	\end{lemma}
381	
382	\begin{proof}
383	Write $y=\zeta_{n'}^a$.  The sum becomes
384	\[
385	        \sum_{a=0}^{n'/2-1}\big(g(\zeta_{n'}^a)-g(-\zeta_{n'}^a)\big)\zeta_{n'}^a.
386	\]
387	The powers $1,\zeta_{n'},\ldots,\zeta_{n'}^{n'/2-1}$ are linearly independent over $\Q$ because $\Phi_{n'}(X)=X^{n'/2}+1$.  Hence every coefficient difference is zero.
388	\end{proof}
389	
390	\begin{theorem}[Inverse quotient theorem over $\C$]\label{thm:upstairs}
391	Let $n=2^m$, $1\le\sigma<n$, and let $M_0$ be the least power of two with $M_0>\sigma$.  Let $S,T\subseteq\mu_n$ have the same cardinality and satisfy
392	\[
393	        e_j(S)=e_j(T)\qquad(1\le j\le\sigma)
394	\]
395	over $\C$.  Then $S\triangle T$ is a union of cosets of the subgroup $\mu_{M_0}\le\mu_n$.  Equivalently, $\mathbf 1_S-\mathbf 1_T$ is constant on $\mu_{M_0}$-cosets.  Conversely, every such quotient rearrangement preserves all $e_j$ for $1\le j<M_0$.
396	\end{theorem}
397	
398	\begin{proof}
399	By Newton identities in characteristic zero, equality of $e_1,\ldots,e_\sigma$ and equality of cardinalities imply equality of the first $\sigma$ power sums.  Thus, for $h=\mathbf 1_S-\mathbf 1_T$,
400	\[
401	        \widehat h(j)=0\qquad(1\le j\le\sigma).
402	\]
403	It is enough to use the dyadic frequencies.  Let $M_0=2^a$.  Since $2^{a-1}\le\sigma$, we have
404	\[
405	        \widehat h(1)=\widehat h(2)=\cdots=\widehat h(2^{a-1})=0
406	\]
407	at the listed dyadic powers.
408	
409	We prove by induction that vanishing at $1,2,\ldots,2^i$ in this dyadic sense forces invariance under $\mu_{2^{i+1}}$.  For $i=0$, $\widehat h(1)=0$ and \Cref{lem:antipodal} give invariance under $\mu_2$.  Suppose $h$ is invariant under $\mu_{2^i}$ and $\widehat h(2^i)=0$.  The map $x\mapsto x^{2^i}$ sends $\mu_n$ onto $\mu_{n/2^i}$ with fibers the $\mu_{2^i}$-cosets.  Let $h^\ast(y)$ be the common value on the fiber above $y$.  Then
410	\[
411	        0=\widehat h(2^i)=2^i\sum_{y\in\mu_{n/2^i}}h^\ast(y)y.
412	\]
413	By \Cref{lem:antipodal}, $h^\ast(y)=h^\ast(-y)$.  Pulling this identity back says that $h$ is invariant under a primitive $2^{i+1}$-st root of unity, hence under $\mu_{2^{i+1}}$.  Iterating to $i=a-1$ gives $\mu_{M_0}$-invariance.
414	
415	For the converse, if $h$ is constant on $\mu_{M_0}$-cosets, then
416	\[
417	        \widehat h(j)=\sum_{\alpha\mu_{M_0}}h(\alpha)\alpha^j\sum_{\kappa\in\mu_{M_0}}\kappa^j=0
418	\]
419	whenever $M_0\nmid j$, in particular for $1\le j<M_0$.  Newton identities convert the corresponding power-sum preservation into preservation of $e_1,\ldots,e_{M_0-1}$ for equal-size subsets.
420	\end{proof}
421	
422	\begin{corollary}[Polynomial size of characteristic-zero fibers]\label{cor:upstairs-poly}
423	Every characteristic-zero prefix fiber in $\binom{\mu_n}{s}$ has size at most
424	\[
425	        2^{n/M_0}\le 2^{n/\sigma}.
426	\]
427	If $\sigma\ge Cn/\log_2n$, then every such fiber has size at most $n^{1/C}$.  With fixed density one may sharpen this to
428	\[
429	        2^{(n/M_0)\HH(\rho)+o(n/M_0)}\le n^{\HH(\rho)/C+o(1)}.
430	\]
431	\end{corollary}
432	
433	\begin{proof}
434	Fix one set $S_0$ in the fiber.  By \Cref{thm:upstairs}, every other set differs from $S_0$ only by toggling whole $\mu_{M_0}$-cosets.  There are $n/M_0$ such cosets.  The entropy refinement counts fixed-weight choices among those quotient cosets.
435	\end{proof}
436	
437	\section{Galois-amplified finite-field collision sieve}\label{sec:galois}
438	
439	We now compare characteristic-zero prefix equality with equality after reduction modulo a split prime.  Let $p\equiv1\pmod n$, choose $\omega\in\F_p^\times$ of order $n$, and reduce $\zeta\mapsto\omega$.
440	
441	For $S,T\subseteq\mu_n$ with exponent sets $A,B\subseteq\Z/n\Z$, define the signed subset polynomial
442	\[
443	        F_{S,T}(X)=\sum_{a\in A}X^a-\sum_{b\in B}X^b\in\Z[X],
444	        \qquad \deg F_{S,T}<n.
445	\]
446	Equality of the first $\sigma$ power sums in $\F_p$ is exactly
447	\[
448	        F_{S,T}(\omega^j)=0\qquad(1\le j\le\sigma).
449	\]
450	If $p>\sigma$, this is equivalent to equality of $e_1,\ldots,e_\sigma$ in $\F_p$.
451	
452	\begin{lemma}[Conjugate-prime amplification]\label{lem:galois-amp}
453	Let $F\in\Z[X]$ have degree $<n$, and assume $F(\zeta)\ne0$.  If
454	\[
455	        F(\omega^j)=0
456	\]
457	for every odd $j\le\sigma$, then
458	\[
459	        p^{\lceil\sigma/2\rceil}\mid \big|\Norm_{\Q(\zeta)/\Q}(F(\zeta))\big|.
460	\]
461	\end{lemma}
462	
463	\begin{proof}
464	Let $\mathfrak p_\omega\subset\Z[\zeta]$ be the degree-one prime ideal corresponding to $\zeta\mapsto\omega$.  For odd $j$, the automorphism $\tau_j:\zeta\mapsto\zeta^j$ is in $\operatorname{Gal}(\Q(\zeta)/\Q)$.  The congruence $F(\omega^j)=0$ says $\tau_j(F(\zeta))\in\mathfrak p_\omega$, equivalently
465	\[
466	        F(\zeta)\in\tau_j^{-1}\mathfrak p_\omega.
467	\]
468	For distinct odd $j$ modulo $n$, these are distinct prime ideals above $p$, each of norm $p$.  There are $\lceil\sigma/2\rceil$ odd integers in $[1,\sigma]$.  Their product divides the principal ideal $(F(\zeta))$, yielding the norm divisibility.
469	\end{proof}
470	
471	The quotient factors must be treated uniformly.  For $M=2^b\mid n$ define
472	\[
473	        Q_M(X)=1+X^{n/M}+X^{2n/M}+\cdots+X^{(M-1)n/M}=\frac{X^n-1}{X^{n/M}-1}.
474	\]
475	Divisibility by $Q_M$ means that the coefficients of $F$ are constant on residue classes modulo $n/M$, i.e. on cosets of the subgroup of order $M$.
476	
477	\begin{theorem}[Galois-amplified no-collision bound]\label{thm:no-collision}
478	There is an absolute constant $C_1$ with the following property.  Let $n=2^m$, $1\le\sigma<n$, $p\equiv1\pmod n$, and $p>\sigma$.  Suppose
479	\[
480	        p>\exp\!\left(C_1\frac{n\log(2n)}{\sigma}\right).
481	\]
482	Then every equality
483	\[
484	        (e_1(S),\ldots,e_\sigma(S))=(e_1(T),\ldots,e_\sigma(T))\quad\text{in }\F_p^\sigma
485	\]
486	for equal-size subsets $S,T\subseteq H=\langle\omega\rangle$ is quotient-periodic: after identifying $H$ with $\mu_n$, the symmetric difference $S\triangle T$ is a union of cosets of a subgroup of order $M>\sigma$.
487	\end{theorem}
488	
489	\begin{proof}
490	Use power sums, which are equivalent because $p>\sigma$.  Let $F=F_{S,T}$.  If $F$ is divisible by $Q_M$ for some $M>\sigma$, then $Q_M(\zeta^j)=0$ for $1\le j\le\sigma$, and this is exactly a quotient-periodic characteristic-zero collision, handled by \Cref{thm:upstairs}.
491	
492	Assume no such quotient divisor with $M>\sigma$ exists.  Let $M$ be the largest power of two such that $F=Q_MG$ with $G\in\Z[X]$; possibly $M=1$.  Then $M\le\sigma$.  Put $\xi=\zeta^M$, a primitive $(n/M)$-th root of unity.  Maximality of $M$ implies $G(\xi)\ne0$; otherwise $\Phi_{n/M}$ would divide $G$ and hence $Q_{2M}$ would divide $F$.
493	
494	For every $\ell\le\sigma/M$, the finite-field equation at $j=M\ell$ gives
495	\[
496	        0=F(\omega^{M\ell})=Q_M(\omega^{M\ell})G((\omega^M)^\ell)=M\,G((\omega^M)^\ell),
497	\]
498	and $M$ is invertible modulo the odd prime $p$.  Applying \Cref{lem:galois-amp} in the smaller field $\Q(\xi)$, with $n$ replaced by $n/M$ and $\sigma$ replaced by $\lfloor\sigma/M\rfloor$, yields
499	\[
500	        p^{\lceil\sigma/(3M)\rceil}\le \big|\Norm_{\Q(\xi)/\Q}(G(\xi))\big|.
501	\]
502	The harmless factor $3$ absorbs the floor and the restriction to odd $\ell$.
503	
504	Since the coefficients of $F$ lie in $\{-1,0,1\}$ and $F=Q_MG$ with $\deg F<n$, the coefficients of $G$ are also in $\{-1,0,1\}$.  Hence every complex conjugate of $G(\xi)$ has absolute value at most $n/M$, and therefore
505	\[
506	        \big|\Norm_{\Q(\xi)/\Q}(G(\xi))\big|
507	        \le (2n)^{\varphi(n/M)}
508	        \le (2n)^{n/(2M)}.
509	\]
510	Thus
511	\[
512	        p^{\sigma/(4M)}\le (2n)^{n/(2M)}
513	\]
514	for all large enough parameters, which implies
515	\[
516	        \log p\le 2\frac{n\log(2n)}{\sigma}
517	\]
518	up to an absolute constant.  Choosing $C_1$ larger gives a contradiction.  Therefore the collision must have had a quotient divisor with $M>\sigma$.
519	\end{proof}
520	
521	\begin{corollary}[Monomial-prefix upper bound in quasi-polynomial split prime fields]\label{cor:quasipoly-upper}
522	Let $n=2^m$, $p\equiv1\pmod n$, $H\le\F_p^\times$ have order $n$, and $s=k+\sigma$.  If
523	\[
524	        p>\exp\!\left(C_1\frac{n\log(2n)}{\sigma}\right),
525	\]
526	then every monomial-prefix word has list size at most
527	\[
528	        2^{n/M_0}\le 2^{n/\sigma},
529	\]
530	where $M_0$ is the least power of two greater than $\sigma$.  In particular, if $\sigma\ge C_0n/\log_2n$, then every monomial-prefix list has size at most $n^{1/C_0+o(1)}$ provided
531	\[
532	        p>\exp\big(O_{C_0}((\log n)^2)\big).
533	\]
534	\end{corollary}
535	
536	\begin{proof}
537	By \Cref{thm:no-collision}, a finite-field prefix fiber coincides with a characteristic-zero quotient fiber.  Apply \Cref{cor:upstairs-poly}.  At $\sigma\ge C_0n/\log_2n$, the threshold on $p$ becomes $\exp(O_{C_0}((\log n)^2))$.
538	\end{proof}
539	
540	\begin{remark}[What the Galois sieve does and does not prove]\label{rem:galois-limit}
541	A one-prime norm sieve --- the mechanism behind the stable range and the density windows of Part~II --- only gives useful information when $p\gg\binom ns^2\operatorname{poly}(n)$.  \Cref{thm:no-collision} is stronger by a factor $\asymp\sigma$ in the exponent because the equations at odd powers give distinct conjugate prime divisors.  Nevertheless it still misses polynomial fields at the critical reserve $\sigma\asymp n/\log n$: then it needs $p>\exp(O((\log n)^2))$, while polynomial fields have $p=\exp(O(\log n))$.  Closing this last factor of $\log n$ requires a genuinely finite-field local-limit theorem, not a norm-divisor argument.
542	\end{remark}
543	
544	\section{The corrected positive conjectures}\label{sec:conjectures}
545	
546	The lower bounds and the quasi-polynomial-field theorem point to the following two-scale statement.  (For \emph{random} evaluation sets, capacity-achieving list decodability is known \cite{BGM23,GZ23}; the content here is the structured smooth-domain case, where \cref{cor:one-scale-false} shows the random prediction is false as stated.)
547	
548	\begin{conjecture}[Prefix local limit with quotient exceptions]\label{conj:prefix-local}
549	Fix $0<\rho<1$, $B>0$, and $\eps>0$.  There is $C=C(\rho,B,\eps)$ such that the following holds for all large smooth $n$.  Let $H\le\F_q^\times$ have order $n$ and generate the ambient field over its prime field, let $k=\rho n$, and let $s=k+\sigma$.  If
550	\[
551	        \sigma\ge C\frac{n}{\log_2n}
552	        \qquad\text{and}\qquad
553	        \sigma\log_2q\ge (1+\eps)\log_2\binom ns,
554	\]
555	then for every $c\in\F_q^\sigma$,
556	\[
557	        \#\{S\in\binom Hs:\Phi_\sigma(S)=c\}\le n^B.
558	\]
559	More sharply, before imposing the second inequality one expects the asymptotic
560	\[
561	        \#\Phi_\sigma^{-1}(c)
562	        \ =\ \frac1{q^\sigma}\binom ns
563	              +\mathrm{Quot}_{\sigma,c}(H,s)
564	              +O(n^B),
565	\]
566	where $\mathrm{Quot}_{\sigma,c}$ is an explicit finite sum of quotient-core contributions from subgroups $K\le H$ with $|K|>\sigma$.
567	\end{conjecture}
568	
569	\begin{conjecture}[Arbitrary locator-fiber local limit]\label{conj:arbitrary-local}
570	Under the same hypotheses as Conjecture~\ref{conj:prefix-local}, for every interpolant $U\in\F_q[X]$ with $\deg U<n$,
571	\[
572	        |\Fib_U(k+\sigma)|\le n^B.
573	\]
574	The predicted pre-threshold asymptotic is the same random-codimension-$\sigma$ law:
575	\[
576	        |\Fib_U(k+\sigma)|
577	        \approx \frac1{q^\sigma}\binom n{k+\sigma}
578	\]
579	except for quotient-periodic and low-denominator structured families.
580	\end{conjecture}
581	
582	\begin{theorem}[Conditional corrected list theorem]\label{thm:conditional-list}
583	If Conjecture~\ref{conj:arbitrary-local} holds, then for generated-field smooth domains
584	\[
585	        \Lst\big(\RS[\F_q,H,k],1-\rho-\sigma/n\big)\le n^B
586	\]
587	whenever
588	\[
589	        \sigma\ge C\frac n{\log n},
590	        \qquad
591	        \sigma\log_2q\ge(1+\eps)\log_2\binom n{k+\sigma}.
592	\]
593	If only Conjecture~\ref{conj:prefix-local} holds, the same conclusion holds for monomial-prefix received words.
594	\end{theorem}
595	
596	\begin{proof}
597	The arbitrary-word claim is exactly \Cref{prop:arb-fiber}.  The monomial-prefix claim is \Cref{prop:monomial-fiber}.
598	\end{proof}
599	
600	\begin{remark}[Subfield correction]\label{rem:subfield}
601	If $H$ is contained in a proper subfield $\F_{q_0}\subsetneq\F_q$, then the entropy scale is governed by the field of definition $q_0$, not the ambient alphabet size $q$.  Indeed, locator coefficients of subsets of $H$ lie in $\F_{q_0}$, and the pigeonhole denominator in \Cref{thm:pigeonhole} is $q_0^\sigma$.  Thus any ambient-$q$ formulation over extension fields is false unless a generated-field hypothesis or a field-of-definition parameter is included.
602	\end{remark}
603	
604	\section{Why pairwise/BCH information is insufficient}\label{sec:pairwise}
605	
606	One tempting approach is to use the fact that equal prefix fibers have large Hamming distance as constant-weight codes.  This gives a useful shadow but not a proof.
607	
608	\begin{lemma}[Pairwise intersection bound]\label{lem:pairwise}
609	Let $S,T\in\binom H{k+\sigma}$ satisfy $\Phi_\sigma(S)=\Phi_\sigma(T)$.  If $S\ne T$, then
610	\[
611	        |S\cap T|\le k-1.
612	\]
613	Equivalently, their constant-weight incidence vectors have Hamming distance at least $2(\sigma+1)$.
614	\end{lemma}
615	
616	\begin{proof}
617	The locators $L_S$ and $L_T$ have the same top $\sigma$ coefficients, so
618	\[
619	        \deg(L_S-L_T)\le (k+\sigma)-\sigma-1=k-1.
620	\]
621	But $L_S-L_T$ vanishes on $S\cap T$.  If $|S\cap T|\ge k$, then $L_S=L_T$, hence $S=T$.
622	\end{proof}
623	
624	At $\sigma\asymp n/\log n$, constant-weight codes of length $n$, weight $\rho n+\sigma$, and distance $2\sigma$ can still be exponentially large by standard Gilbert--Varshamov type packings.  Therefore any proof of Conjecture~\ref{conj:prefix-local} must exploit the algebraic subgroup moment equations, not merely the pairwise distance pattern.  This is the precise sense in which BCH minimum-distance information is too weak.
625	
626	
627	\part{Slack mutual correlated agreement: the corrected theory}
628	
629	\section{The list-side ledger, and the MCA comparison point}\label{sec:interface}
630	
631	Part~I established the corrected list-side ledger: the coefficient-pigeonhole and quotient-core lower bounds (\cref{thm:pigeonhole,thm:qcore}), the prime-field refutation of the one-scale ambient-$q$ entropy-gap prediction (\cref{cor:one-scale-false}), the quotient-core profile and the corrected list conjecture (\cref{def:qprofile,conj:listprofile}), the characteristic-zero inverse quotient theorem (\cref{thm:upstairs}), and the Galois-amplified quasi-polynomial split-prime positive theorem (\cref{cor:quasipoly-upper}).  That ledger is the right comparison point for the MCA conjecture of \cref{sec:boundary}.  Recall that $\Lst(C,\delta)$ denotes the worst-case list size at relative radius $\delta$; in this part $p$ is prime unless stated otherwise.
632	
633	\begin{remark}[MCA versus list decoding]\label{rem:mcalist}
634	The quotient-core construction refutes the one-scale list prediction directly.  It does not by itself refute any MCA statement: it inflates the number of codewords explaining one received word, never the number of bad slopes of a line.  Nevertheless the same quotient scales enter the conservative MCA formulation of \cref{conj:B} through the profile $\mathcal Q$.  \Cref{thm:qnecessity} below shows that, above the quotient norm threshold and up to the explicit constant $\HH(\rho)/\beta(\rho)$, this quotient profile is genuinely necessary for polynomial MCA slope bounds.  The remaining open direction is sufficiency, especially for arbitrary residue-line data at a fixed prime.
635	\end{remark}
636	
637	\section{Definitions, and the two delimitations}\label{sec:noslack}
638	
639	\begin{definition}[Support-wise agreement]\label{def:sclose}
640	For $C\subseteq\F^D$, $|D|=n$, $\delta\in[0,1]$: a word $u\in\F^D$ is \emph{$S$-close} to $C$ at radius $\delta$ if $S\subseteq D$, $|S|\ge(1-\delta)n$, and $u|_S=c|_S$ for some $c\in C$.
641	\end{definition}
642	
643	\begin{definition}[Bad parameter and line-MCA error]\label{def:mca}
644	For a line $u_z=f+zg$, $z\in\F$: the parameter $z$ is \emph{support-wise MCA-bad} at radius $\delta$ if there is $S\subseteq D$ with (i) $u_z$ $S$-close to $C$ at radius $\delta$, and (ii) no pair $c_f,c_g\in C$ satisfying $f|_S=c_f|_S$ and $g|_S=c_g|_S$.  Then
645	\[
646	        \emca(C,\delta)\ =\ \max_{f,g\in\F^D}\ \frac1{|\F|}\,\#\{z:\ z\text{ support-wise MCA-bad for }f+zg\},
647	\]
648	and the threshold is
649	\[
650	        \delta^*_C(\eps^*)=\sup\{\delta:\emca(C,\delta)\le\eps^*\}.
651	\]
652	A witness at radius $\delta$ is one at every larger radius (neither condition mentions $\delta$ otherwise), so $\emca(C,\cdot)$ is nondecreasing and error one propagates upward; this is the monotonicity lemma of \cite{NoSlack}.
653	\end{definition}
654	
655	For a degree-$c$ tuple $\mathbf u=(u_0,\dots,u_c)$ and $u(z)=\sum_jz^ju_j$, the parameter $z$ is \emph{curve-bad} if some $S$ has $u(z)|_S\in C|_S$ while not every $u_j$ has $u_j|_S\in C|_S$; $\eps^{(c)}_{\rm mca}$ is the corresponding error.
656	
657	The no-slack form of the up-to-capacity principle --- $\emca(C,\delta)\le\mathrm{negl}(q)$ for every $\delta<1-\rho$ --- fails on smooth domains: error one holds on the interval $[1-\rho-1/N,1]$ whenever some divisor $N\mid n$ has $\rho N\in\Z$ and $\rho(1-\rho)N^2\ge p$ (so for the deployed FFT primes at $N=2^{18}$), the error is $1-1/p$ at radius $1-\rho-1/(2\log_2n)$ on the Fermat fields $q=n+1$ with $p\in\{17,257,65537\}$ at rates $1/2$ and $1/4$, and infinitely many primes carry power-of-two subgroups of order $\Theta(\log p)$ with error at least $(\log_2p)^{-6}$ at gap $1/N$ \cite{NoSlack}.  Concurrent near-capacity failure results over prime-field multiplicative subgroups \cite{KKH26,Kambire26} apply related pressure through different mechanisms.  We will recover and considerably extend the first of these from the slack calculus below.  Two elementary results delimit the field-size dependence and force the shape of any true formulation.
658	
659	\begin{theorem}[One bad parameter per support]\label{thm:onez}
660	For any linear code, any line, and every $S\subseteq D$: at most one $z$ is bad with witness $S$, at any radius.  Hence $\emca(C,\delta)\le\#\{S:\ |S|\ge(1-\delta)n,\ C|_S\ne\F^S\}/q\le2^n/q$, and if $q\ge2^n/\eps^*$ then $\delta^*_C(\eps^*)=1$ exactly: over very large fields the no-slack principle holds trivially, for every line.
661	\end{theorem}
662	
663	\begin{proof}
664	Condition (ii) of \cref{def:mca} does not involve $z$; if it fails for $S$, no $z$ has witness $S$.  If it holds with $g|_S\in C|_S$ (so $f|_S\notin C|_S$): $u_z|_S\in C|_S$ would force $f|_S\in C|_S$.  If $g|_S\notin C|_S$ and $z_1\ne z_2$ both had $u_{z_i}|_S\in C|_S$: subtracting, $(z_1-z_2)g|_S\in C|_S$, impossible.  Supports with $C|_S=\F^S$ (for Reed--Solomon: all $|S|\le k$, by interpolation) admit no witness since (ii) fails there.
665	\end{proof}
666	
667	\begin{proposition}[Tangent floor]\label{prop:floor}
668	For $C=\RS[\F,D,k]$ and $\delta\in(0,1-\rho)$ with $m=\lfloor\delta n\rfloor\le q$:
669	$\emca(C,\delta)\ \ge\ m/q$.
670	\end{proposition}
671	
672	\begin{proof}
673	Fix $E\subseteq D$, $|E|=m$, codewords $P_1,P_2$, and $f=P_1+e_f$, $g=P_2+e_g$ with errors supported on $E$, $e_g\equiv1$ there and $e_f$ injective there.  For $x\in E$ put $z_x=-e_f(x)$ and $S_x=(D\setminus E)\cup\{x\}$: the error of $u_{z_x}$ against the codeword $P_1+z_xP_2$ vanishes at $x$ and off $E$, so condition (i) holds; a codeword explaining $g$ on $S_x$ would agree with $P_2$ on $n-m>k$ points, hence equal $P_2$, contradicting $g(x)\ne P_2(x)$: condition (ii).  The $m$ slopes $z_x$ are distinct and bad.
674	\end{proof}
675	
676	\begin{remark}[The phase transition, and the forced shape of the theory]\label{rem:phase}
677	For protocol-size fields $q=O(n)$ the floor alone gives $\emca\ge\Theta(\delta)$ at every radius, so no fixed-$\eps^*$ threshold statement can hold there, and even for $q=\mathrm{poly}(n)$ the floor forces an additive $n/q$-scale correction into any positive conjecture; for $q\ge2^n/\eps^*$ the question trivializes.  The live regime is $\mathrm{poly}(n)\le q\le2^{o(n)}$, the correct positive target is an error of the form $n^{1+o(1)}/q$, and --- because of the failure results above --- the radius must carry a slack reserve.  This fixes the object of study: the bad-slope sets of lines at radius $1-\rho-t/N$.
678	\end{remark}
679	
680	\section{The slack calculus}\label{sec:calculus}
681	
682	\subsection{The exact characterization}
683	
684	\begin{definition}[The multi-symmetric image]\label{def:badset}
685	For $1\le T\le n-k$, $\delta_T=1-(k+T)/n$ and
686	\[
687	        \mathcal B_T(D,k)\ =\ \big\{(-1)^Te_T(S):\ S\subseteq D,\ |S|=k+T,\ e_1(S)=\cdots=e_{T-1}(S)=0\big\}.
688	\]
689	For $T=1$ this is $-(k+1)^{\wedge}D$.
690	\end{definition}
691	
692	\begin{theorem}[Exact slack characterization]\label{thm:exactslack}
693	Let $D$ be \emph{any} evaluation set of size $n$ in a field $\F$, $C=\RS[\F,D,k]$, $1\le T\le n-k$.  For the line $u_z=x^{k+T}+z\,x^k$, the set of support-wise MCA-bad parameters at radius $\delta_T$ is \emph{exactly} $\mathcal B_T(D,k)$: the line's error contribution is $|\mathcal B_T(D,k)|/q$, with error one iff $\mathcal B_T(D,k)=\F$.
694	\end{theorem}
695	
696	\begin{proof}
697	($\subseteq$)  If $z$ is bad, $u_z$ agrees with some $R$, $\deg R<k$, on a set $S$ with $|S|\ge k+T$.  The polynomial $P_z=X^{k+T}+zX^k-R$ is monic of degree $k+T$ with at least $k+T$ roots: exactly $k+T$, so $|S|=k+T$ and $P_z=L_S$.  Comparing coefficients in degrees $k+T-j$ for $1\le j\le T-1$ (absent from both $u_z$ and $R$) gives $e_j(S)=0$; the degree-$k$ coefficient gives $z=(-1)^Te_T(S)$.
698	
699	($\supseteq$)  If $z=(-1)^Te_T(S)$ with $S$ as in \cref{def:badset}, then $L_S=X^{k+T}+zX^k+R_S$ with $\deg R_S<k$, so $u_z$ agrees with the codeword $-R_S$ on the $k+T$ points of $S$.  Condition (ii): $g=x^k$ has degree exactly $k$, and two distinct polynomials of degree $\le k$ agree on at most $k<k+T$ points, so no codeword explains $g$ on $S$ --- (ii) holds for every witness set of more than $k$ points, regardless of $f$.
700	\end{proof}
701	
702	The restricted-sumset description of the no-slack failures is therefore not an artifact of any proof method: it is the precise answer, and at every slack $T$ the object to control is $\mathcal B_T$.
703	
704	\subsection{Quotients, and the collapse of symmetric witnesses}
705	
706	\begin{lemma}[Quotient locator]\label{lem:tlocator}
707	Let $D\le\F^\times$ of order $n$, $N\mid n$, $a=n/N$, $Q=D^a$ the quotient subgroup of order $N$, $a\mid k$, $\ell=k/a+t\le N$.  For $A\subseteq Q$, $|A|=\ell$:
708	\[
709	        L_A(X)\ :=\ \prod_{b\in A}(X^a-b)\ =\ X^{k+ta}+\sum_{j=1}^t(-1)^je_j(A)\,X^{k+(t-j)a}+R_A(X),
710	        \qquad\deg R_A<k,
711	\]
712	and $L_A$ vanishes on $S_A=\{x\in D:\ x^a\in A\}$, of size $k+ta$.  (Expand $\prod_b(Y-b)$ at $Y=X^a$: the displayed terms sit in degrees $a(\ell-j)$, and all remaining degrees are below $a(\ell-t)=k$.)
713	\end{lemma}
714	
715	\begin{theorem}[Slack-$t$ lower bound]\label{thm:slackt}
716	With $V_t(Q,\ell)=\{z:\ \exists A\subseteq Q,\ |A|=\ell,\ e_1(A)=\cdots=e_{t-1}(A)=0,\ (-1)^te_t(A)=z\}$: every $z\in V_t(Q,\ell)$ is bad for the line $f=x^{k+ta}$, $g=x^k$ at radius $1-\rho-t/N$, so $\emca(\RS[\F,D,k],1-\rho-t/N)\ge|V_t(Q,\ell)|/q$, with error one when $V_t=\F$.  If $\mathrm{char}\,\F>t$ the defining conditions are equivalent, by the Newton identities, to $p_1(A)=\cdots=p_{t-1}(A)=0$ and $p_t(A)=-tz$.
717	\end{theorem}
718	
719	\begin{proof}
720	\Cref{lem:tlocator} gives $L_A=X^{k+ta}+zX^k+R_A$, so $u_z$ agrees with $-R_A$ on $S_A$; condition (ii) as in \cref{thm:exactslack}.  The fiber-union structure makes $e_j(S_A)=0$ automatic for $a\nmid j$, so $S_A$ is a $\mathcal B_{ta}$-witness with exactly the displayed quotient conditions surviving.
721	\end{proof}
722	
723	\begin{remark}[Strict subfamily]\label{rem:strict}
724	$\mathcal B_{ta}(D,k)\supseteq V_t(Q,\ell)$, and the containment can be strict: at $p=17$, $n=16$, $\rho=1/2$, $T=2$, the quotient family ($a=2$, $N=8$, $\ell=5$) covers $16$ of the $17$ values and an asymmetric $D$-witness supplies the missing $z=0$ (verified exhaustively; \cref{app:verify}).
725	\end{remark}
726	
727	\begin{proposition}[Coset collapse: symmetric slack is no slack]\label{prop:collapse}
728	Let $p>d$, $K\le Q$ of order $d$, $d\mid\ell$, and let $A$ be a union of $\ell/d$ distinct $K$-cosets.  Then $p_j(A)=0$ for all $d\nmid j$ --- in particular $e_1(A)=\cdots=e_{d-1}(A)=0$ automatically --- and $e_d(A)=(-1)^{d-1}\sum_iy_i$ with $y_1,\dots,y_{\ell/d}$ the distinct $d$-th powers of coset representatives.  Hence the union-of-coset part of $V_d(Q,\ell)$ equals, up to an explicit nonzero scalar, the slack-\emph{one} value set $m^{\wedge}(Q^d)$ at quotient order $N/d$, $m=\rho(N/d)+1$: subgroup-symmetric witnesses produce nothing beyond the one-condition ladder.
729	\end{proposition}
730	
731	\begin{proof}
732	$\sum_{\kappa\in K}(x\kappa)^j=x^j\sum_\kappa\kappa^j$, which is $dx^j$ if $d\mid j$ and $0$ otherwise; sum over cosets, convert by Newton ($p>d$); distinct cosets biject with distinct $d$-th powers; and $\ell/d=\rho(N/d)+1$ at $\ell=\rho N+d$.
733	\end{proof}
734	
735	New slack content therefore requires \emph{asymmetric} witnesses with vanishing leading symmetric functions.  The next two theorems prove that the two global models which decide no-slack questions --- lifting to characteristic zero, and lifting to short digit ranges --- cannot see them, even at $t=2$.
736	
737	\begin{theorem}[Cyclotomic rigidity]\label{thm:rigidcyclo}
738	Let $N=2^s$ and $A\subseteq\mu_N\subseteq\Z[\zeta_N]$ with $p_1(A)=0$ in $\Z[\zeta_N]$.  Then $A$ is a union of antipodal pairs $\{\omega,-\omega\}$.  Consequently every characteristic-zero witness for $V_2$ is of coset type, and the characteristic-zero slack-$2$ value set is exactly the ladder rung $2\cdot m^{\wedge}(\mu_{N/2})$.
739	\end{theorem}
740	
741	\begin{proof}
742	In the power basis $1,\zeta,\dots,\zeta^{N/2-1}$, $\sum_{a\in A}a=\sum_jc_j\zeta^j$ with $c_j=\mathbf1[\zeta^j\in A]-\mathbf1[-\zeta^j\in A]\in\{-1,0,1\}$; vanishing forces $c\equiv0$, i.e.\ each antipodal pair is contained in or disjoint from $A$.  Then $p_2(A)=2\sum_{\rm pairs}\zeta^{2j}$.
743	\end{proof}
744	
745	\begin{theorem}[Digit rigidity on Fermat fields]\label{thm:rigidfermat}
746	Let $p=2^M+1$ be a Fermat prime, $Q=\langle2\rangle=\{\pm2^j:0\le j<M\}\le\F_p^\times$, and $A\subseteq Q$ with $\sum_{a\in A}a\equiv0\pmod p$.  Then $A$ is a union of antipodal pairs.
747	\end{theorem}
748	
749	\begin{proof}
750	The sum lifts to $s=\sum_jc_j2^j$, $c_j\in\{-1,0,1\}$, with $|s|\le2^M-1<p$, so $s=0$; uniqueness of binary representations forces $c\equiv0$.
751	\end{proof}
752	
753	\begin{remark}[Where the difficulty lives]\label{rem:wall}
754	Asymmetric elements of $V_t$ require cancellations of size comparable to $p$ --- genuinely modular, i.e.\ subgroup equidistribution.  \Cref{sec:pool} pushes equidistribution as far as current exponential-sum technology reaches; \cref{sec:rigidity} develops the characteristic-zero theory at every slack, which governs the deepest level; \cref{sec:boundary} proves where these methods stop.
755	\end{remark}
756	
757	\subsection{Certified slack thresholds, and curve transfer}
758	
759	\begin{lemma}[Dias da Silva--Hamidoune \cite{DH94}; polynomial-method proofs in \cite{ANR96,Alon99}]\label{lem:dsh}
760	For every $A\subseteq\F_p$ with $|A|=m$ and every $1\le h\le m$:
761	$|h^{\wedge}A|\ \ge\ \min\{p,\ h(m-h)+1\}$.
762	\end{lemma}
763	
764	\begin{corollary}[Certified slack at the root barrier]\label{cor:certified}
765	Let $0<\rho\le1/2$ and let $N_{\rm full}(p,n,\rho)$ be the smallest divisor $N\mid n$ with $\rho N\in\Z$, $\ell=\rho N+1\le N$, and $\ell(N-\ell)+1\ge p$.  For every divisor $N\ge N_{\rm full}$ with $\rho N\in\Z$:
766	\[
767	        \emca\Big(\RS[\F_p,D,\rho n],\ 1-\rho-\tfrac1N\Big)\ =\ 1,
768	\]
769	hence error one on the interval $[1-\rho-1/N_{\rm full},\,1]$, with $N_{\rm full}\le(1+o(1))\sqrt{p/\rho(1-\rho)}$ when such divisors exist (automatic on smooth $n$ of that size).  (\Cref{lem:dsh} makes $V_1(Q,\ell)=-\ell^{\wedge}Q=\F_p$; \cref{thm:slackt} at $t=1$; monotonicity for the interval.)
770	\end{corollary}
771	
772	\begin{theorem}[Curve transfer]\label{thm:curve}
773	Let $\varphi(Z)=\sum_{j=1}^c\varphi_jZ^j$ be nonconstant with $\varphi(0)=0$, and consider the degree-$c$ tuple $u_0=x^{k+a}$, $u_j=\varphi_jx^k$.  Every $z$ with $\varphi(z)\in-\ell^{\wedge}Q$ is curve-bad at radius $1-\rho-1/N$, so
774	$\eps^{(c)}_{\rm mca}\ge1-c(1-|\ell^{\wedge}Q|/q)$ there: whenever $\ell^{\wedge}Q=\F$, \emph{every} $z$ is curve-bad and $\eps^{(c)}_{\rm mca}=1$ on the whole interval, for every degree $c\ge1$.  Every slack floor proved for lines transfers to every curve class containing polynomial reparametrizations of lines.
775	\end{theorem}
776	
777	\begin{proof}
778	$u(z)=x^{k+a}+\varphi(z)x^k$; choose $A$ with $\sum A=-\varphi(z)$ and apply \cref{lem:tlocator} at $t=1$.  For condition (ii) one unexplained member suffices: any $u_j=\varphi_jx^k$ with $\varphi_j\ne0$ is explained on at most $k<|S_A|$ points.  Count preimages of $\varphi$; monotonicity is verbatim for tuples.
779	\end{proof}
780	
781	\section{The two-moment certificate, and fullness at the root barrier}\label{sec:twomoment}
782	
783	The Dias da Silva--Hamidoune theorem is the $t=1$ engine of the restricted-sum ladder, and its exterior-algebra proof invites an upgrade to the joint map $S\mapsto(e_1(S),e_2(S))$ on a multiplicative subgroup.  The exact finite object keeps the subgroup relations and becomes a cyclic reduced alternant; and an elementary two-stage construction already gives \emph{full} two-moment coverage at the square-root barrier, at every prime.
784	
785	Let $Q\le\F_p^\times$ have even order $N$.  For $S\in\binom Q\ell$ set $\Psi_2(S)=(e_1(S),e_2(S))$; for $a\in\F_p$ let $\Pi_a(T)=1-(T-a)^{p-1}$ (the indicator of $T=a$); and put
786	\[
787	        \Delta(X)=\prod_{i<j}(X_j-X_i),\qquad E_1=\sum_iX_i,\qquad E_2=\sum_{i<j}X_iX_j,
788	        \qquad F_{a,b}=\Delta\cdot\Pi_a(E_1)\,\Pi_b(E_2).
789	\]
790	
791	\begin{theorem}[Exact reduced $t=2$ certificate]\label{thm:certificate}
792	For every $(a,b)\in\F_p^2$:
793	\[
794	        (a,b)\in\Psi_2\tbinom Q\ell
795	        \iff
796	        F_{a,b}(X)\not\equiv0\pmod{X_1^N-1,\dots,X_\ell^N-1}.
797	\]
798	\end{theorem}
799	
800	\begin{proof}
801	Since $p\nmid N$, $X^N-1$ has the distinct root set $Q$, so $\F_p[X]/(X_i^N-1)$ is the function algebra on $Q^\ell$.  On a tuple in $Q^\ell$, $\Delta$ is nonzero exactly when the entries are distinct; on distinct tuples, $\Pi_a(E_1)\Pi_b(E_2)$ is nonzero exactly when the underlying set has $(e_1,e_2)=(a,b)$.
802	\end{proof}
803	
804	Equivalently, with $A_N=\F_p[u]/(u^N-1)$, alternants identified with $\bigwedge^\ell A_N$, $\mathsf E_1,\mathsf E_2$ acting by multiplication by $e_1,e_2$, and $\omega_\ell=1\wedge u\wedge\cdots\wedge u^{\ell-1}$: the condition is $\Pi_a(\mathsf E_1)\Pi_b(\mathsf E_2)\,\omega_\ell\ne0$ --- a reduced cyclic exterior-algebra nonvanishing problem.  Resolving it below the root barrier is open; at the barrier, no machinery is needed:
805	
806	\begin{theorem}[Two-moment fullness in the square-root range]\label{thm:twomoment}
807	Let $Q\le\F_p^\times$ have even order $N$ and write $\ell=h+2r$.  If
808	\[
809	        h(N-h)+1\ \ge\ p
810	        \qquad\text{and}\qquad
811	        r\Big(\frac N2-h-r\Big)+1\ \ge\ p,
812	\]
813	then $\Psi_2\binom Q\ell=\F_p^2$.  Consequently, for $\ell=\rho N+O(1)$, full two-moment coverage holds whenever
814	\[
815	        p\ \le\ \Big(\frac{\rho(1-\rho)}5-o(1)\Big)N^2 ,
816	\]
817	i.e.\ for all $N\ge(1+o(1))\sqrt{5p/\rho(1-\rho)}$ --- at every prime, with no thresholds.
818	\end{theorem}
819	
820	\begin{proof}
821	Fix $(a,b)$.  By \cref{lem:dsh} on $Q$, the first hypothesis gives an $h$-set $B\subseteq Q$ with $e_1(B)=a$.  Since $N$ is even, $-1\in Q$ and the squaring map on $Q$ is two-to-one onto the index-two subgroup $Q^2$ of order $N/2$; let $A_B=Q^2\setminus B^2$, of size at least $N/2-h$.  By \cref{lem:dsh} on $A_B$, the second hypothesis gives an $r$-set $R\subseteq A_B$ with $\sum_{y\in R}y=e_2(B)-b$.  For each $y\in R$ choose $x_y\in Q$ with $x_y^2=y$; since $y\notin B^2$, neither $x_y$ nor $-x_y$ lies in $B$, and pairs over distinct $y$ are disjoint (their elements square to distinct values).  Put $S=B\sqcup\bigsqcup_{y\in R}\{x_y,-x_y\}$, of size $h+2r=\ell$.  Each antipodal pair has $e_1=0$ and $e_2=-x_y^2=-y$; pairs of pairs and pair-versus-$B$ cross terms cancel ($e_2$ of a disjoint union is $e_2+e_2'+e_1e_1'$, and all the pair blocks have $e_1=0$).  Hence
822	\[
823	        e_1(S)=e_1(B)=a,\qquad e_2(S)=e_2(B)-\sum_{y\in R}y=b .
824	\]
825	For the constant, set $h=\alpha N+O(1)$, $r=(\rho-\alpha)N/2+O(1)$: the two hypotheses read $p\le\alpha(1-\alpha)N^2$ and $p\le(\rho-\alpha)(1-\rho-\alpha)N^2/4$, and the balance equation $4\alpha(1-\alpha)=(\rho-\alpha)(1-\rho-\alpha)=\rho(1-\rho)-\alpha+\alpha^2$ simplifies to $5\alpha(1-\alpha)=\rho(1-\rho)$: the balanced value is exactly $\alpha(1-\alpha)=\rho(1-\rho)/5$.
826	\end{proof}
827	
828	\begin{corollary}[Every slack-two monomial line fails at the root barrier, at every prime]\label{cor:twomomentmca}
829	Let $a=n/N$, $a\mid k$, $\ell=\rho N+2$, with the hypotheses of \cref{thm:twomoment} satisfiable at this $\ell$ (in particular $N\ge(1+o(1))\sqrt{5p/\rho(1-\rho)}$).  Then for \emph{every} base $c\in\F_p$, the line
830	\[
831	        u_z\ =\ x^{k+2a}+c\,x^{k+a}+z\,x^{k}
832	\]
833	has every slope $z$ support-wise MCA-bad at radius $1-\rho-2/N$: error one on the whole slack-two monomial family, at every prime.
834	\end{corollary}
835	
836	\begin{proof}
837	\Cref{thm:twomoment} supplies $A\subseteq Q$, $|A|=\ell$, with $(-e_1(A),e_2(A))=(c,z)$; \cref{lem:tlocator} turns $A$ into an agreement set for $u_z$, and condition (ii) holds as always via $g=x^k$.  (Parity of $\ell-h$ is absorbed in the $O(1)$'s.)
838	\end{proof}
839	
840	\begin{remark}[Ledger]\label{rem:twomomentledger}
841	\Cref{thm:twomoment} strengthens, at slack two, both ends of the unconditional ladder: \cref{thm:descent} covers only the diagonal base $c=0$ (at constant $2$ in place of $\sqrt5$), and \cref{thm:ladder} reaches smaller $N$ only with thresholds in $p$.  It is not the entropy-scale result: the conjectural $t=2$ target asks for coverage when $\log_2p\lesssim\tfrac12\HH(\rho)N$, far beyond $p\asymp N^2$; \cref{thm:certificate} identifies the exact finite nonvanishing problem that going further requires.  Verified: at $(p,N,h,r)=(31,30,2,3)$, $\ell=8$, the construction of \cref{thm:twomoment} built witnesses for all $961$ targets $(a,b)\in\F_{31}^2$ with zero failures, and exhaustive enumeration of all $\binom{30}8$ subsets confirms $\Psi_2$ is onto (\cref{app:verify}).
842	\end{remark}
843	
844	\section{The failure ladder, I: the free pool}\label{sec:pool}
845	
846	One lemma drives all the equidistribution-based failure results.  For a subgroup $K\le\F_p^\times$ of order $d$ and $\vec s\in\F_p^t$ write $S_K(\vec s)=\sum_{\kappa\in K}e_p\big(\sum_{m\le t}s_m\kappa^m\big)$.
847	
848	\begin{lemma}[Free pool]\label{lem:pool}
849	Let $t\ge1$, and suppose $K\le Q\le\F_p^\times$, $|K|=d$, $|Q|=N$, satisfy the equidistribution hypothesis
850	\[
851	        \max_{\vec s\ne0}\,|S_K(\vec s)|\ \le\ d\,p^{-\nu}
852	        \qquad\text{for some }\nu>0 .
853	\]
854	Put $C=\lceil(t-\log_pd)/\nu\rceil+6$ and suppose $d\ge4C^2$ and $p^{2\nu}\ge2$.  Then for every $\ell$ with $C\le\ell\le N-d$ and every $\vec v\in\F_p^t$ there is $A\subseteq Q$ with $|A|=\ell$ and $p_m(A)=v_m$ for all $m\le t$: all power-sum fibers are nonempty.  In particular $V_t(Q,\rho N+t)=\F_p$ and, by \cref{thm:slackt}, the MCA error at radius $1-\rho-t/N$ is one.
855	\end{lemma}
856	
857	\begin{proof}
858	Fix $\vec v$.  Choose any $B_0\subseteq Q\setminus K$ with $|B_0|=\ell-C$ (possible since $\ell-C\le N-d$) and set $\vec w=\vec v-(p_1(B_0),\dots,p_t(B_0))$.  For $j\ge2$ let $T_j(\vec w)=\#\{(x_1,\dots,x_j)\in K^j:\ \sum_ix_i^m=w_m\ \forall m\le t\}$.  Orthogonality gives $T_j(\vec w)=p^{-t}\sum_{\vec s}S_K(\vec s)^je_p(-\langle\vec s,\vec w\rangle)$, and the $t$-dimensional Parseval identity reads $\sum_{\vec s}|S_K(\vec s)|^2=p^t\,\#\{(\kappa,\kappa'):\kappa^m=\kappa'^m\ \forall m\le t\}=p^td$, since the $m=1$ equation already forces $\kappa=\kappa'$.  Hence
859	\[
860	        \Big|T_j(\vec w)-\frac{d^{\,j}}{p^{t}}\Big|
861	        \ \le\ \big(\max_{\vec s\ne0}|S_K(\vec s)|\big)^{j-2}\cdot p^{-t}\sum_{\vec s\ne0}|S_K(\vec s)|^{2}
862	        \ \le\ \big(dp^{-\nu}\big)^{j-2}d .
863	\]
864	For $j\in\{C-2,C\}$ the main term dominates by a factor $2$: $d^{\,j}/p^t\ge2(dp^{-\nu})^{j-2}d$ is equivalent to $d\,p^{\nu(j-2)}\ge2p^{t}$, and $j-2\ge C-4\ge(t-\log_pd)/\nu+2$ gives $dp^{\nu(j-2)}\ge p^{t+2\nu}\ge2p^t$.  So $T_j(\vec w)\in[d^{\,j}/(2p^t),\,2d^{\,j}/p^t]$ for these $j$.  Tuples counted by $T_C(\vec w)$ with two equal coordinates number at most $\binom C2\sum_{y\in K}T_{C-2}(\vec w-(2y,2y^2,\dots,2y^t))\le C^2d^{\,C-1}/p^t$, which is at most $\tfrac12\cdot d^{\,C}/(2p^t)$ once $d\ge4C^2$.  Some tuple therefore has $C$ pairwise distinct coordinates in $K$ with the prescribed power sums; adjoin $B_0$.
865	\end{proof}
866	
867	Three exponential-sum inputs instantiate the hypothesis.
868	
869	\begin{theorem}[Conditional polynomial range from a free-pool input]\label{thm:ladder}
870	Let $D\le\F_p^\times$ be smooth of order $n$, $C=\RS[\F_p,D,\rho n]$, and fix a divisor scale $N\mid n$ with quotient subgroup $Q$ of order $N$.  Assume that $Q$ contains a subgroup $K$ of order $d$ for which the exponential-sum hypothesis of \cref{lem:pool} holds for the relevant degree $t$, with a saving $\nu>0$, and that $\ell=\rho N+t$ satisfies
871	\[
872	        C(t,d,p,\nu)\le \ell\le N-d,
873	\]
874	where $C(t,d,p,\nu)=\lceil(t-\log_p d)/\nu\rceil+6$ is the pool size from \cref{lem:pool}.  Then
875	\[
876	        \emca(C,1-\rho-t/N)=1 .
877	\]
878	In particular, the following are valid wherever the cited exponential-sum estimates supply the displayed hypothesis with the quoted savings.
879	\begin{enumerate}[label=(\roman*),leftmargin=2.2em]
880	\item For every fixed $\delta>0$ and fixed $t\ge1$, the Bourgain--Glibichuk--Konyagin and Bourgain estimates \cite{BGK06,Bourgain05}, in the required polynomial-phase form, imply error one for all sufficiently large $p$ and all $N\ge p^\delta$.
881	\item For $t=1$, Shkredov's medium-range subgroup estimate \cite{Shk14}, in the above form, gives explicit pool sizes in the range $N\ge4p^{1/3+\eps}$; sample pool sizes retained from the computation are $C(0.50)=18$, $C(0.45)=25$, $C(0.40)=42$, $C(0.36)=102$.
882	\item For fixed $t\ge2$, the small-subgroup Weil bounds of Ostafe--Shparlinski--Voloch \cite{OSV24}, in the required polynomial-phase form, give explicit pool sizes in the range $N\ge p^{3/7+\eps}$; sample sizes retained from the computation are $C(2,0.50)=168$, $C(2,0.55)=99$, $C(3,0.55)=1563$, $C(3,0.60)=726$.  The growing-slack statement is conditional on the same recursion remaining uniform up to
883	\[
884	        t\le(1+o(1))\frac{\log\log p}{\log\log\log p}.
885	\]
886	\end{enumerate}
887	\end{theorem}
888	
889	\begin{proof}
890	The theorem is exactly \cref{lem:pool} followed by \cref{thm:slackt}.  The enumerated ranges are not independent algebraic arguments; they require the cited exponential-sum bounds in the precise uniform form stated in \cref{lem:pool}.  This is why the result is recorded as conditional on that input rather than as a self-contained fixed-prime equidistribution theorem.
891	\end{proof}
892	
893	\section{The failure ladder, II: descent, and the dichotomy}\label{sec:descent}
894	
895	The pool method needs thresholds in $p$.  At \emph{dyadic} slack, an exact identity removes them entirely.
896	
897	\begin{theorem}[Dyadic descent: error one at every dyadic slack, DSH grade]\label{thm:descent}
898	Let $p$ be prime, $D\le\F_p^\times$ have order $n$, let $N\mid n$, put $a=n/N$, and let $Q=D^a$ have order $N$.  Assume $a\mid k$, $k/a=\rho N\in\Z$.  Let $t$ be a power of two with $t\mid N$, and assume
899	\[
900	        \ell=\rho N+t\le N,
901	        \qquad t\mid \ell
902	        \quad\text{equivalently } t\mid\rho N .
903	\]
904	For $B\subseteq Q^t$ with $|B|=\ell/t$, the orbit union
905	\[
906	        A=\{x\in Q:\ x^t\in B\}
907	\]
908	satisfies
909	\[
910	        e_j(A)=0\quad(t\nmid j),
911	        \qquad e_t(A)=-e_1(B)
912	\]
913	(for even $t$; for odd $t$ the nonzero scalar is absorbed into the slope).  Consequently
914	\[
915	        \{e_t(A): |A|=\ell,\ e_1(A)=\cdots=e_{t-1}(A)=0\}
916	        \supseteq -\big(\tfrac\ell t\big)^{\wedge}(Q^t).
917	\]
918	If
919	\[
920	        \frac\ell t\left(\frac Nt-\frac\ell t\right)+1\ge p,
921	\]
922	then the monomial slack-$t$ line has
923	\[
924	        \emca\Big(\RS[\F_p,D,k],1-\rho-\frac tN\Big)=1.
925	\]
926	In particular, for fixed $\rho$ and fixed dyadic $t$, this holds whenever
927	\[
928	        N\ge(t+o(1))\sqrt{p/\rho(1-\rho)},
929	\]
930	subject to the divisibility assumptions above.
931	\end{theorem}
932	
933	\begin{proof}
934	The $t$-power map $Q\to Q^t$ is exactly $t$-to-one and its fibers are the $\mu_t$-orbits.  Therefore
935	\[
936	        \prod_{a\in A}(X-a)=\prod_{y\in B}(X^t-y),
937	\]
938	a polynomial in $X^t$.  Hence all elementary symmetric coefficients whose indices are not divisible by $t$ vanish.  The coefficient of $X^{\ell-t}$ gives $e_t(A)=-e_1(B)$ for even $t$ with the stated harmless sign convention.  Dias da Silva--Hamidoune applied to the subgroup $Q^t$ of order $N/t$ gives full coverage of $\F_p$ when the displayed inequality holds.  The conclusion follows from \cref{thm:slackt}.
939	\end{proof}
940	
941	\begin{remark}[What descent adds]\label{rem:descenth}
942	The radius $1-\rho-t/N=1-\rho-1/(N/t)$ coincides with the slack-one rung on the quotient $Q^t$ (\cref{prop:collapse} read in reverse), already reachable by \cref{cor:certified}; the content is the \emph{fiber-level} statement that every diagonal target $(0,\dots,0,z)$ of the slack-$t$ system is hit, by explicit witnesses, at DSH grade --- the correct baseline against which \cref{thm:ladder} must be measured (its gain is the non-diagonal targets and witness asymmetry, at the cost of thresholds in $p$), and the load-bearing input for the positive theorems' floors below.  Verified at $p=193$, $N=64$, $t=2$, $\ell=34$: the identities, and coverage of all $193$ residues by $e_1$ over the $\binom{32}{17}$ subsets of $Q^2$ (\cref{app:verify}).
943	\end{remark}
944	
945	The characteristic-zero theory of \cref{sec:rigidity} will show (\cref{thm:dichotomy}) that descent witnesses are the \emph{only} characteristic-zero diagonal witnesses at dyadic slack, and that at non-dyadic slack none exist at all.
946	
947	\section{The rigidity theory at every slack}\label{sec:rigidity}
948	
949	From here $p\equiv1\pmod n$, $n=2^m$, and $\mathfrak p\subseteq\Z[\zeta_n]$ is a fixed degree-one prime over $p$, identifying $H\le\F_p^\times$ with $\mufn$.  For $h:\mufn\to\Z$ write $\widehat h(j)=\sum_xh(x)x^j\in\Z[\zeta_n]$.  For a slack level $\sigma$, $M_0=2^a$ is the least power of two exceeding $\sigma$ and $N_0=n/M_0$.
950	
951	The engine is the antipodal identity, \cref{lem:antipodal}, proved in \cref{sec:upstairs}: for $n'$ a power of two and $g:\mu_{n'}\to\Z$, the relation $\sum_yg(y)\,y=0$ forces $g(y)=g(-y)$ for all $y$.  The theorem below is the integer-valued form of \cref{thm:upstairs}: the same dyadic induction applies to arbitrary $h:\mufn\to\Z$, not only to indicator differences, and the optimality of the modulus is recorded.
952	
953	\begin{theorem}[Inverse quotient theorem, integer-valued form]\label{thm:rigidity}
954	Let $2\sigma<n$ and $h:\mufn\to\Z$ with $\widehat h(2^i)=0$ for $0\le i<a$ (implied by $\widehat h(j)=0$ for all $1\le j\le\sigma$, since $2^{a-1}\le\sigma$).  Then $h$ is invariant under $\mu_{M_0}$.  Conversely, every $\mu_{M_0}$-invariant $h$ has $\widehat h(j)=0$ for every $M_0\nmid j$.  The modulus is optimal: $\mu_{M_0}$-coset differences across distinct $\mu_{2M_0}$-cosets witness every $\sigma\le M_0-1$.
955	\end{theorem}
956	
957	\begin{proof}
958	Induction on the dyadic frequencies: $\widehat h(1)=\cdots=\widehat h(2^i)=0$ forces invariance under $\mu_{2^{i+1}}$.  Base: \cref{lem:antipodal} at $n'=n$ gives $h(x)=h(-x)$.  Step: $h$ invariant under $\mu_{2^i}$; the map $x\mapsto x^{2^i}$ has fibers the $\mu_{2^i}$-cosets, on which $h$ is constant with common value $h^*$, and
959	$0=\widehat h(2^i)=2^i\sum_{y\in\mu_{n'}}h^*(y)\,y$ with $n'=n/2^i\ge4$.  \Cref{lem:antipodal} gives $h^*(y)=h^*(-y)$; choosing $\omega$ with $\omega^{2^i}=-1$ (present since $2^{i+1}\le M_0\mid n$), $h(x)=h^*(x^{2^i})=h^*(-x^{2^i})=h(\omega x)$, so $h$ is invariant under $\langle\mu_{2^i},\omega\rangle=\mu_{2^{i+1}}$.  Converse: $\sum_{\kappa\in\mu_{M_0}}\kappa^j=0$ for $M_0\nmid j$.
960	\end{proof}
961	
962	\Cref{thm:rigidcyclo} is the case $\sigma=1$: the antipodal mechanism propagates dyadically rather than stalling.  Three consequences are used throughout.  \emph{Witness classification}: $A\subseteq\mufn(\mathbb C)$ with $e_1(A)=\cdots=e_{\sigma'}(A)=0$ in $\Z[\zeta]$ is a union of $\mu_{M_0'}$-orbits, $M_0'$ the least $2$-power exceeding $\sigma'$ (Newton converts $e$- to $p$-conditions in characteristic zero).  \emph{Class cap}: subsets with equal $\Z[\zeta]$-prefixes $(e_1,\dots,e_\sigma)$ differ by $\mu_{M_0}$-coset rearrangement, and the class of a set with $a$ cosets inside and $b$ outside has size exactly $\sum_u\binom au\binom bu=\binom{a+b}a\le2^{N_0}$.  \emph{Norm bound}: a nonzero $\widehat h(j)$ has all archimedean conjugates of modulus at most $\|h\|_1$, so $0<|\Norm_{\Q(\zeta)/\Q}\widehat h(j)|\le\|h\|_1^{\,n/2}$ --- the bridge from characteristic zero to $\F_p$: a mod-$\mathfrak p$ coincidence that fails in $\Z[\zeta]$ (a \emph{collision}) forces $p$ to divide a bounded nonzero integer.  The lattice identity $\{\widehat h(j)=0,\ j\le\sigma\}=\{\mu_{M_0}\text{-invariant}\}$ was verified by exact linear algebra at $n=16$ and $n=32$ across five slack levels (\cref{app:verify}).
963	
964	\begin{theorem}[Witness dichotomy: non-dyadic slack is collision-only]\label{thm:dichotomy}
965	Let $t\ge2$, $2(t-1)<n$, and $A\subseteq\mufn(\mathbb C)$ with $e_1(A)=\cdots=e_{t-1}(A)=0$ in $\Z[\zeta]$.
966	\begin{enumerate}[label=(\roman*),leftmargin=2.2em]
967	\item If $t$ is a power of two: $A$ is a union of $\mu_t$-orbits --- the descent witnesses of \cref{thm:descent} are the \emph{only} characteristic-zero diagonal witnesses, and they realize exactly the values \cref{thm:descent} realizes.
968	\item If $t$ is not a power of two: $M_0'>t$, the converse half of \cref{thm:rigidity} forces $p_t(A)=0$, and Newton then $e_t(A)=0$: characteristic-zero witnesses with $z\ne0$ \emph{do not exist}.  Every mod-$p$ witness with $z\ne0$ is a collision: any unconditional non-dyadic slack claim is an instance of the collision problem --- consistent with \cref{thm:ladder}(iii) operating only at $p\le N^{7/3}$, where collisions abound.
969	\end{enumerate}
970	Verified exhaustively at $n=16$, $t=3$, $\ell=8$: all six characteristic-zero zero-prefix subsets are $\mu_4$-orbit unions, with $e_3=0$ (\cref{app:verify}).
971	\end{theorem}
972	
973	\section{Positive theorems: the density regime}\label{sec:positive}
974	
975	We now work at the deepest level: $N=n$, dyadic slack $\sigma$ with $\sigma\mid k$, $s=k+\sigma$, and radius $1-\rho-\sigma/n$.  When one writes $\sigma\asymp Cn/\log_2 n$, the invariant quantity is
976	\[
977	        \ceff=\frac{\sigma\log_2 n}{n},
978	        \qquad\text{so that}\qquad
979	        \frac n\sigma=\frac{\log_2n}{\ceff},
980	        \quad 2^{n/\sigma}=n^{1/\ceff}.
981	\]
982	All asymptotic statements below are expressed in terms of $\ceff$; if $\sigma=(1+o(1))Cn/\log_2n$, then $\ceff=C+o(1)$.
983	
984	By \cref{thm:exactslack} read coefficientwise, the bad slopes of the line $u_z=U_{c^0}+zX^{s-j}$ through the base
985	\[
986	        U_{c^0}=X^s+\sum_{i<\sigma}(-1)^ic^0_iX^{s-i}
987	\]
988	in direction $j\in[1,\sigma]$ are exactly
989	\[
990	        \big\{(-1)^j(e_j(A)-c^0_j):
991	        A\in\tbinom Hs,
992	        e_i(A)=c^0_i\ \text{for all }i\in[1,\sigma]\setminus\{j\}\big\},
993	\]
994	with $c^0_j=0$ at $j=\sigma$ or for the zero base.  Condition (ii) of \cref{def:mca} is automatic on witness sets of more than $k$ points.  Write $B(p)$ for the bad-slope count of the canonical line ($c^0=0$, $j=\sigma$).
995	
996	\begin{theorem}[The canonical line, two-sided]\label{thm:diag}
997	\begin{enumerate}[label=(\roman*),leftmargin=2.2em]
998	\item\emph{(Unconditional floor, every prime.)}
999	\[
1000	        B(p)\ge \min\left\{p,\ \frac s\sigma\left(\frac n\sigma-\frac s\sigma\right)+1\right\}
1001	        =\rho(1-\rho)\left(\frac{\log_2n}{\ceff}\right)^2+O\left(\frac{\log n}{\ceff}\right),
1002	\]
1003	realized by the descent witnesses of \cref{thm:descent} at $t=\sigma$, $N=n$.
1004	\item\emph{(Density ceiling.)}  For every $X\ge n^2\binom ns$ and at least half the primes $p\equiv1\pmod n$ in $(X,2X]$ (Siegel--Walfisz \cite{Dav00}; ineffective threshold),
1005	\[
1006	        B(p)\le
1007	        \underbrace{\min\left\{p,\ \binom{n/\sigma}{s/\sigma}\right\}}_{\text{descent slopes}}
1008	        +O_\rho(\log n).
1009	\]
1010	Thus the canonical line's error contribution is at most
1011	\[
1012	        \frac{n^{1/\ceff}+O(\log n)}{p}\to0
1013	\]
1014	whenever $p$ is in such a window and $\ceff$ is bounded away from zero.
1015	\end{enumerate}
1016	\end{theorem}
1017	
1018	\begin{proof}
1019	Part (i) is \cref{thm:descent} and \cref{lem:dsh}.  For (ii), \cref{thm:rigidity} at level $\sigma-1$ has modulus $\sigma$ because $\sigma$ is dyadic.  Thus every characteristic-zero witness with $p_1(A)=\cdots=p_{\sigma-1}(A)=0$ is a $\mu_\sigma$-orbit union, hence a descent witness.  There are at most $\binom{n/\sigma}{s/\sigma}\le2^{n/\sigma}=n^{1/\ceff}$ such descent slopes.  Every other bad slope is carried by a collision single: a set $A$ for which some nonzero cyclotomic integer $\widehat{\mathbf 1_A}(i)$, $i\le\sigma-1$, vanishes modulo $\mathfrak p$.  Its norm is at most $n^{n/2}$, so it has at most $\kappa=\lceil n\log n/(2\log X)\rceil$ prime divisors exceeding $X$.  Summing over all $s$-subsets and dividing by the number $\gg X/(n\log X)$ of admissible primes gives the asserted $O_\rho(\log n)$ bound for at least half the primes.
1020	\end{proof}
1021	
1022	\begin{theorem}[All monomial bases, canonical direction]\label{thm:allbases}
1023	For every $X\ge n^2\binom ns^2$ and at least half the primes $p\equiv1\pmod n$ in $(X,2X]$, simultaneously for every base $c^0\in\F_p^{\sigma-1}$, the canonical-direction line $U_{c^0}+zX^k$ has
1024	\[
1025	        \#\{\text{bad }z\}
1026	        \le |\Phi_{\sigma-1}^{-1}(c^0)|
1027	        \le 2^{n/\sigma}+O(\sqrt{\log n})
1028	        =n^{1/\ceff}+O(\sqrt{\log n}),
1029	\]
1030	where $\Phi_{\sigma-1}(A)=(e_1(A),\dots,e_{\sigma-1}(A))$ on $s$-subsets.
1031	\end{theorem}
1032	
1033	\begin{proof}
1034	Bad slopes refine the slab $\Phi_{\sigma-1}^{-1}(c^0)$ by the last coordinate $e_\sigma$, so their number is at most the slab size.  In characteristic zero, any two sets in the same slab differ by a $\mu_\sigma$-coset rearrangement; each class has size at most $P=2^{n/\sigma}$.  Let $C_p^{(\sigma-1)}$ count ordered pairs of $s$-subsets that have equal punctured prefixes modulo $\mathfrak p$ but not in $\Z[\zeta]$.  For a slab of size $x$,
1035	\[
1036	        x^2\le Px+C_p^{(\sigma-1)},
1037	        \qquad\text{hence}\qquad
1038	        x\le P+\sqrt{C_p^{(\sigma-1)}}.
1039	\]
1040	For an ordered pair not equal in characteristic zero, choose the first nonzero prefix difference.  Its norm is bounded by $(2s)^{n/2}$, so it is divisible by at most $\kappa\ll n\log n/\log X$ primes exceeding $X$.  Summed over $\binom ns^2$ ordered pairs and averaged over the admissible primes in $(X,2X]$, the assumption $X\ge n^2\binom ns^2$ gives $C_p^{(\sigma-1)}=O(\log n)$ for at least half the primes.  This proves the displayed bound.
1041	\end{proof}
1042	
1043	\begin{remark}[Accounting the floor]\label{rem:flooracct}
1044	The floor in \cref{thm:diag}(i) consists of quotient-periodic witnesses: quotient-codeword agreements, the natural candidates for what a final protocol definition of ``mutual explanation'' might absorb.  Thus there are two numbers to track: the raw bad-slope count, which has a descent floor of order $(\log n/\ceff)^2$ at every prime and, by \cref{prop:qfloor}, a quotient-exact floor of order $n^{\beta(\rho)/\ceff(1-o(1))}$ above a quasipolynomial quotient threshold; and the aperiodic collision count, which is $O(\log n)$ for most primes in the density windows.  Which number is operational depends on the protocol definition.
1045	\end{remark}
1046	
1047	\section{The direction-arithmetic of slack}\label{sec:directions}
1048	
1049	Fix the zero base and vary the direction: bad slopes of $X^s+zX^{s-j}$ are carried by $A$ with $e_i(A)=0$ for $i\in[1,\sigma]\setminus\{j\}$ and $e_j(A)=\pm z$.
1050	
1051	\begin{lemma}[Ramification parity]\label{lem:parity}
1052	Let $B\subseteq\mu_{N}$, $N$ a power of two, $|B|=s'$.  Modulo the ramified prime $\lambda=(1-\zeta_{N})$ of $\Z[\zeta_{N}]$ \cite{Was97}, every root of unity is $\equiv1$, so $e_i(B)\equiv\binom{s'}i\pmod\lambda$: $e_i(B)=0$ forces $\binom{s'}i$ even.  Moreover $\binom{s'}i$ is even for all $2\le i\le\sigma'$ if and only if $s'\equiv0$ or $1\pmod{M'}$, $M'$ the least power of two exceeding $\sigma'$.
1053	\end{lemma}
1054	
1055	\begin{proof}
1056	The congruence is immediate.  Lucas, both directions: if $s'\equiv0,1\pmod{M'}$, every $i\in[2,M'-1]$ has a set bit in positions $1,\dots,\log_2M'-1$ where $s'$ has none, so $\binom{s'}i$ is even.  If $s'\equiv r\in[2,M'-1]$: for $r\le\sigma'$ take $i=r$; for $r>\sigma'$ the top bit of $r$ sits at $M'/2$, and $i=r-M'/2$ (if $\ge2$) or $i=M'/2$ lies in $[2,\sigma']$ with bits inside $r$'s, making $\binom{s'}i$ odd.
1057	\end{proof}
1058	
1059	\begin{theorem}[Direction trichotomy]\label{thm:directions}
1060	Dyadic slack $\sigma$, zero base, direction $1\le j\le\sigma$.
1061	\begin{enumerate}[label=(\roman*),leftmargin=2.2em]
1062	\item $j=\sigma$ (canonical): the two-sided descent band of \cref{thm:diag}.
1063	\item $j$ non-dyadic: the constraints contain every dyadic frequency up to $\sigma$; \cref{thm:rigidity} forces $\mu_{M_0}$-invariance with $M_0>\sigma\ge j$, hence $e_j(A)=0$: \emph{no characteristic-zero slopes $z\ne0$ exist}; for most primes in the window of \cref{thm:diag}, the bad-slope count is $O_\rho(\log n)$, all collision-borne.
1064	\item $j$ dyadic, $j<\sigma$: the constraints at levels below $j$ force $\mu_j$-invariance, so $j\nmid s$ gives no witnesses at all; for $j\mid s$, the identity $\prod_{a\in A}(X-a)=\prod_{y\in B}(X^j-y)$ reduces the problem \emph{exactly} to the direction-one problem at slack $\sigma'=\sigma/j$, size $s'=s/j$, on $\mu_{n/j}$: find $B$ with $e_2(B)=\cdots=e_{\sigma'}(B)=0$ and $e_1(B)\ne0$.
1065	\item Direction one: characteristic-zero witnesses require $s'\equiv0,1\pmod{M'}$ (\cref{lem:parity}).  Conversely they exist for $s'\equiv1\pmod{M'}$ at every $\sigma'$ --- take $B=\{y\}\sqcup(\mu_{M'}\text{-orbits})$, which has $e_i(B)=e_i(\{y\})=0$ for $i\ge2$ --- and for $s'\equiv0\pmod4$ at $\sigma'=2$: the quadruple $\{y,\,iy,\,\zeta_8y,\,-\zeta_8y\}$, whose six pairwise products $iy^2,\pm\zeta_8y^2,\pm i\zeta_8y^2,-iy^2$ cancel in pairs, padded by $\mu_4$-orbits.  At $\sigma'=2$ the classification is therefore complete: witnesses exist iff $s'\equiv0,1\pmod4$.  When witnesses exist they persist at \emph{every} prime ($e_1(B)\ne0$ in $\Z[\zeta]$ has finitely many prime divisors), and the scaling $A\mapsto uA$, $u\in H$, spreads $e_j$ over at least $n/j$ values: at least $n/j$ bad slopes forever.  When the parity obstructs: $O_\rho(\log n)$ bad slopes for most primes.
1066	\end{enumerate}
1067	\end{theorem}
1068	
1069	\begin{proof}
