1529	\section{Subfield confinement over extension fields}\label{sec:subfield}
1530	
1531	Deployed instantiations sample the slope from an extension field $\F=B^{\,d}$ of the base field $B$ containing the domain.  The following confinement theorem shows the entire prime-field witness theory deflates by a factor $|B|/|\F|$ in that setting, while the list-side obstructions persist --- so the two grand challenges genuinely decouple over extensions.  A two-radius refinement of \cref{thm:subfield}, covering the proximity-loss form of correlated agreement, is proved in \cite[Lem.\ ``subfield confinement'']{UniversalCap}.
1532	
1533	\begin{theorem}[Subfield confinement]\label{thm:subfield}
1534	Let $B\le\F$ be a subfield, $D\subseteq B$, $C=\RS[\F,D,k]$, and let $f,g\in B^D$ be $B$-valued words.  Then every support-wise MCA-bad parameter of the line $f+zg$, at every radius, lies in $B$.
1535	\end{theorem}
1536	
1537	\begin{proof}
1538	Fix a $B$-basis $e_1=1,e_2,\dots,e_d$ of $\F$ and the $B$-linear coordinate projections $\pi_i:\F\to B$.  For $P\in\F[X]_{<k}$ and $x\in D\subseteq B$ we have $\pi_i(P(x))=(\pi_iP)(x)$, where $\pi_iP$ applies $\pi_i$ to coefficients; each $\pi_iP$ is a codeword.  Let $z\notin B$, so $z=\sum_iz_ie_i$ with $z_{i_0}\ne0$ for some $i_0\ge2$, and let $S$ be any set on which $f+zg$ agrees with a codeword $P$.  Comparing coordinates on $S$: the $i_0$-th coordinate of $(f+zg)(x)=f(x)+zg(x)$ is $z_{i_0}g(x)$, so $g|_S=(z_{i_0}^{-1}\pi_{i_0}P)|_S$, and the first coordinate is $f(x)+z_1g(x)$, so $f|_S=(\pi_1P-z_1z_{i_0}^{-1}\pi_{i_0}P)|_S$.  Both explaining polynomials have degree $<k$, so $f$ and $g$ are simultaneously explained on $S$ itself, and $z$ fails condition (ii) of \cref{def:mca} for every candidate $S$.
1539	\end{proof}
1540	
1541	\begin{corollary}[Deflation of the prime-field witness theory]\label{cor:deflate}
1542	In the sextic-extension instantiation discussed in \cite{ABF26} ($\F=B^6$ over a $31$-bit base field, $D\subseteq B$), every line with $B$-valued $f,g$ --- in particular every monomial line and every witness line constructed in Parts~I--II --- contributes MCA error at most $|B|/|\F|=p^{-5}<2^{-154}<2^{-128}$.
1543	\end{corollary}
1544	
1545	\begin{corollary}[Decoupling]\label{cor:decouple}
1546	List obstructions do not deflate: $C_B:=\RS[B,D,k]\subseteq C$ and a $B$-valued received word has $C$-list at least its $C_B$-list, so the quotient-core lists of \cref{thm:qcore} persist verbatim over $\F$.  Consequently, at deployed extension parameters, lists stay superpolynomial while every MCA attack below $2^{-128}$ must use genuinely $\F$-valued line data --- and such data exists nonconstructively, since \cref{thm:cap} applies to $q=|\F|\le2^{256}$ directly; sharper, the deployed-parameter corollary of \cite{UniversalCap} certifies $\eca>2^{-22}$ at gap $2^{-7}$ on the sextic itself.
1547	\end{corollary}
1548	
1549	\begin{remark}[Where the explicit $\F$-valued attack should live]\label{rem:explicitattack}
1550	By \cref{thm:subfield} the residue-line normal form of \cref{thm:normalform} is the natural source: denominators $E\in\F[X]$ not defined over $B$ evade confinement, and the quotient locator calculus applies to them unchanged.  Making the $\F$-valued bad lines explicit over the deployed sextic extension is the concrete open target: by \cite{UniversalCap} such lines exist nonconstructively already at gap $2^{-7}$ with bad-slope density $>2^{-22}$, and exhibiting them is posed there as the explicit-lines problem.
1551	\end{remark}
